<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton comes out in favor of Northeast home heating oil reserve  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton says she
wants to be "the kind of leader who lifts people up, not pushes them down."
<P>
	   Calling on New Yorkers to "reject the politics of division, revenge and
retribution," Clinton asked more than 1,000 blacks and Hispanics on Sunday to
support her campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Without mentioning her Republican rival, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, by name, Clinton warned against the politics of "insulting people and
demeaning people."
</P>
<P>
	   "This must be one New York," the first lady told the annual dinner hosted by
the state Legislature's Black and Puerto Rican Caucus.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Sunday, Clinton called for New York and the other Northeastern
states to have their own home heating oil reserves just in case future shortages
make prices skyrocket again.
</P>
<P>
	   "We in the Northeast ... are the most reliant on home heating oil and
therefore pay the highest prices when we have cold snaps," said the Senate
candidate who just moved to New York in January as the coldest weather of the
winter hit.
</P>
<P>
	   "We'd be able to dip into that reserve without raising the strategic issues
that are raised by going to the reserve that we already have."
</P>
<P>
	   A coalition of Northeastern lawmakers, including Democrats and Republicans,
have already called for creation of such a regional reserve.
</P>
<P>
	   With OPEC countries limiting production, the cost of home heating oil in New
York has risen from a statewide average of 90.6 cents a gallon in February of
last year to $2.01 a gallon as of last week. The Northeast has been hardest hit
by the price increases.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani has been lambasting President Clinton for refusing to dip into the
nation's strategic oil reserves to ease the price crunch on consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration says the reserves are only for emergencies and
are not intended as a way to affect market price.
</P>
<P>
	   However, candidate Clinton said she and the president know what New Yorkers
are going through.
</P>
<P>
	   "I take this issue very personally as does the president," said Clinton, who
recently moved into the couple's $1.7 million home in Chappaqua in Westchester
County. "Now that we are homeowners here in New York, our house is heated by
heating oil and it is extremely expensive."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton noted that she and her husband are better able to afford the high
oil prices than most New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
	   For the short term, Clinton said New York's congressional delegation should
support President Clinton's call for $600 million in emergency assistance to
help poor people meet heating-oil costs. The first lady also said she favored
dipping into the strategic reserves with a swap system under which U.S. oil
companies would be able to borrow from the stockpile and make larger donations
back to it later.
</P>
<P>
	   That way, "they would not run into some of the legal and security issues,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said she would also support a bill by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
that would require home heating oil companies to keep a larger reserve of their
own.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had a mild winter last year, so that the oil companies did not stockpile
enough of an inventory," she said. "So when OPEC began to raise prices, they had
to scramble on the open market and pay more."
</P>
<P>
	   In a sign of how serious the situation is in New York, the Pataki
administration last week used a waiver to allow the use of high-sulfur heating
oil at New York City municipal facilities. Sulfur levels in heating oil are
tightly regulated by state environmental regulations to protect air quality in
the metropolitan area. Connecticut and New Hampshire have used sulfur waivers
similar to New York's during the heating oil crunch, the Pataki administration
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton also called on the OPEC counties to increase oil production.
</P>
<P>
	   That would "enable us to cut prices so that we wouldn't face either higher
prices in the short term in the home heating oil or longer term in gasoline
prices," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 0004 </TRAILER>
