<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Hillary Clinton at side, courts minority votes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - On the eve of his crucial debate with Bill Bradley
at Harlem's Apollo theater, Al Gore sought to reinforce his standing among New
York's minorities.
<P>
	   Renewing his call for an end to racial profiling by police and passage of
federal hate crimes legislation, the vice president told a largely black
audience of more than 800 people at an Albany church Sunday that the Republicans
who hope to take the White House are "morally blind" to racial concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, campaigning for the first time this year in New York with first lady
and Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton, never mentioned his Democratic
rival for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   But in an uncharacteristically impassioned speech, the vice president
lambasted the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are those who have 20/20 vision who are morally blind ... Some of
those individuals just left the state of South Carolina," Gore said to laughter
from the audience at the Wilborn Temple First Church of God in Christ.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing the Confederate battle flag that flies over the South Carolina state
Capitol, Gore paraphrased a Bob Dylan song and said, "They looked at that flag
and they turned their heads and pretended that they just didn't see."
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president said the Republican reaction - both Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Sen. John McCain have said the flag issue is something to be resolved
by South Carolinians - reminded him of those who say that America has become
color blind.
</P>
<P>
	   "They use their color blind the way duck hunters use their duck blinds -
they hide behind it and hope the ducks won't know what they're up to," he said
to cheers.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore and the first lady, running against New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, had warm words and hugs for each other.
</P>
<P>
	   "Her vision will make a difference ... I will stand up for her," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one in America is more qualified to lead us than our vice president,"
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore left the Albany church after about a half-hour of handshaking to fly to
New York City where he met Sunday afternoon with the editorial board of The
Amsterdam News, an influential black-oriented newspaper whose endorsement the
vice president is courting.
</P>
<P>
	   The three-hour church service was part of the annual weekend conference
sponsored by the state Legislature's black and Hispanic caucus that brings
together hundreds of the state's top black and Hispanic leaders. They represent
an increasingly powerful voting bloc in New York state. Blacks and Hispanics
made up 15 percent of voters in the state's 1998 election for governor and U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   A big test of that minority voting power will come in the state's March 7
primary, which is considered a major showdown for Gore and Bradley, a former New
York Knicks basketball star. Both have made major appeals to minorities in their
bids for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   While there has been speculation that Gore and the first lady didn't want to
be seen together as they work to escape the long shadow of President Clinton,
aides to both have denied that is true.
</P>
<P>
	   In a brief interview Sunday with The Associated Press, Clinton said she was
"just honored to help him in any way that I can. I was grateful for the chance
to appear with him, because I don't get to see him so often now that he's all
over the country. We used to work together very closely on a lot of issues ...
I'm very fond of him personally as well as very supportive of him as our next
president."
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   AP Writer Jesse J. Holland contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 0004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
