<DOCNO> APW20000221.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blake in His America's Cup Farewell  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Sir Peter Blake's mark is all over Auckland.
</P>
<P>
	Red socks.
</P>
<P>
	There are real ones, worn by everyone from sailing enthusiasts to bikers.
There's a giant red sock perched on a waterfront building. The day before the
scheduled start of the America's Cup, a parade of boats, with large red socks
dangling from the masts, sailed past the harbor to salute Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
	Red socks?
</P>
<P>
	If Blake, the CEO of Team New Zealand, can whip up the same fervor in his next
endeavor as head of the Cousteau Society, the world's oceans should be in good
shape.
</P>
<P>
	Red socks became Team New Zealand's lucky symbol in the 1995 America's Cup in
San Diego, when Blake wore them aboard Black Magic during the challenger trials.
The one day he wasn't on the boat was the only time the Kiwis lost on the water
(one victory was overturned on protest).
</P>
<P>
	Someone noticed and the lucky red socks craze soon spread through New Zealand.
Eager to support their team, New Zealanders bought 100,000 pairs of red socks in
a matter of days, with half the money going to Team New Zealand's coffers. The
Kiwis went on to whip Dennis Conner in the finals, just the second time the
America's Cup was taken from America.
</P>
<P>
	It was such a big victory that Blake was knighted.
</P>
<P>
	Five years later, the red socks stir is still here.
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's sort of a national icon. Crazy thing, but it doesn't do any harm,''
Blake said.
</P>
<P>
	Team New Zealand still relies on proceeds from sales of the socks -- made in
Korea, by the way -- in its effort to retain the Cup. The Kiwis got off to a
great start Sunday when Black Magic beat Italy's Luna Rossa by 1 minute, 17
seconds in the opening race, which was delayed a day by lack of wind.
</P>
<P>
	Monday was a day off, and racing resumes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	So it's one win down and, Blake hopes, four to go in his America's Cup career.
After this, his third America's Cup, he's off to lead the Cousteau Society, an
environmental organization founded in 1973 by the late undersea explorer
Jacques-Yves Cousteau.
</P>
<P>
	Although he's one of the world's most accomplished sailors, Blake, 51, never
really considered himself an America's Cup sailor. He's not on the boat this
time, but when he sailed on Black Magic in 1995, he epitomized the Kiwis'
low-key approach by basically doing grunt work even though he was the syndicate
chief.
</P>
<P>
	Going around buoys is pretty tame stuff for a guy who's sailed around the world
several times. It's largely because of that experience that he accepted the job
with the Cousteau Society.
</P>
<P>
	``I was planning to do something similar of my own a number of years ago
anyway, so it'll be good to be involved with this,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
	Blake will be involved with planning and fundraising -- much like he does with
his America's Cup campaign -- but he also plans to spend six months a year on
the water. After the America's Cup, he plans to go to Greenland. Next year, he
wants to explore the Northwest Passage above Canada.
</P>
<P>
	Blake used to sail around the world as fast as he could. He won one Whitbread
Round the World race and in 1994 won the Jules Verne Trophy by sailing nonstop
around the globe on a catamaran in 74 days, 22 hours, 17 minutes and 22 seconds.
The record fell three years later to a Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
	Blake will now slow down and, using TV, film and the Internet, share some of
the sights he's seen -- massive waves, icebergs, whales and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen lots of things I want to show kids,'' Blake said. ``I've gone,
`wow,' `fantastic' and `marvelous.' I want to capture some of those now, and get
young people interested in the environment.
</P>
<P>
	``It's more excitement and adventure entertainment rather than a scientific
survey. Otherwise, they'll change channels.''
</P>
<P>
	Blake said the most awe-inspiring thing he's seen on the oceans is the weather.
</P>
<P>
	``I want to show people what it's like to be in a full storm at sea. You may
say, `why bother?' But weather is probably the most talked about subject in the
world. And most people probably don't know how it develops or why it's there.
There's a lot to do with water.''
</P>
<P>
	Same goes for the next several days. Blake has one last item to try to add to
his resume -- the first successful America's Cup defense by a country other than
the United States.
</P>
<P>
	``I'm leaving the America's Cup pretty happy -- as long as one thing happens,''
Blake said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 0054 </TRAILER>
