<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Items in 'the Nation's Attic'  </HEADLINE>
   By CARL HARTMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Smithsonian Institution added 345,000 items to its
collection of historical artifacts last year, an eclectic mix ranging from the
earliest known portrait of Thomas Jefferson to the leather pants, boots, jacket
and brassiere of murdered Tejano singer Selena.
</P>
<P>
	   Including stamps, buttons and dried insects, the 15 museums and a zoo run by
the Smithsonian own more than 141 million objects and living creatures. Despite
all that space, only a small fraction can go on display; the rest is squirreled
away in research centers.
</P>
<P>
	   Given its vast collections, the Smithsonian has earned the nickname ``the
nation's attic.''
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, Lawrence M. Small, the new secretary of the Smithsonian,
announced a reorganization designed in part to get more of the treasures
traveling around the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   At the end of each year, the staff takes several weeks to count up all the
items the Smithsonian has purchased, discovered, given birth to and found left
on its many doorsteps. Then it makes an announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the most cuddly acquisitions in 1999 were Mike, Chrissie and Eric,
Sumatran tiger cubs born in June at Washington's National Zoo. It's the third
litter for the mother, Kerinci. They'll probably go to other zoos eventually.
</P>
<P>
	   There's also Kwame, a male lowland gorilla born to Mandara in November.
</P>
<P>
	   As for Jefferson, he was serving as U.S. minister to France in 1768 when he
had his likeness painted. The portrait belonged to John Adams, his predecessor
as president. They had a bitter political quarrel but reconciled before both
died on the same day: July 4, 1826, the 50th anniversary of his Declaration of
Independence, which Jefferson had written.
</P>
<P>
	   A descendant of Adams left the heirloom to the National Portrait Gallery,
one of the Smithsonian museums.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mexican-American singer Selena Quintanilla-Perez was 23 when she was
shot to death in 1995. Yolanda Saldivar, former president of her fan club, was
sentenced to life in prison for the murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 0200 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
