<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela-Led Burundi Talks Resume  </HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG NELSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- Scolding negotiators trying to end Burundi's
7-year-old civil war, Nelson Mandela accused them of squabbling while their
fellow countrymen were massacred every day.
</P>
<P>
	   The former South African president's 90-minute address last month in this
northern Tanzanian town left little doubt among the negotiators or anyone else
that he meant business.
</P>
<P>
	   Now Mandela is under pressure to deliver. And with the talks set to resume
today, his skills will be tested as he tries to advance an effort to end
fighting between Burundi's Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu rebels that has killed
more than 200,000 people since 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite Mandela's reproaches, representatives of the 18 political groups
participating in the talks quarreled last week in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, over
the same issues that have mired down the talks for months: integrating rebels
into the army and guidelines for future national elections.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile in Burundi, there were reports last week of army massacres of
scores of Hutu civilians near Ruyigi, as more than 345,000 Hutus remained
confined to army-run camps and restricted from tending their land during the
year's main planting season.
</P>
<P>
	   More importantly, middle-class Tutsis -- President Pierre Buyoya's key base
of support -- grew restive as recent price increases on fuel and other staples
continued to strain their already threadbare household budgets.
</P>
<P>
	   No hard-nosed negotiations were expected during Mandela's three-day stay in
Arusha. Instead, he will play the impresario, briefing regional leaders on the
progress of the talks and hosting President Clinton and French President Jacques
Chirac by television hookup from their respective capitals.
</P>
<P>
	   By focusing international attention on the talks, Mandela hopes to prod
negotiators toward a settlement and secure outside interest in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
	   Some observers criticized the high-tech, video diplomacy as time-wasting
nonsense, saying any accord will emerge from a more discreet, parallel
negotiating track with the two main rebel groups, which so far have not
participated in the Arusha process.
</P>
<P>
	   The suggestion was denied with a chuckle by Judge Mark Bomani, Mandela's
chief aide to the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A show is a good thing sometimes to create the climate for painstaking
negotiations,'' he said. ``The participants will get the message that the
outside world is watching.''
</P>
<P>
	   Then there is the issue of Mandela's record as a diplomat. For all his
accomplishments, he failed in peace initiatives to Zaire -- now the Democratic
Republic of Congo -- Sudan and Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
	   Even if Mandela manages to brokers an agreement here in the coming months, a
key element has so far been excluded from the process: Burundians themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   With the exception of an elite few among the country's minority Tutsi and
majority Hutu, most of Burundi's 6.2 million people know little of the progress
of the talks. What they do know rests mainly on rumor and state-controlled
radio.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Negotiators could come to some agreement, but there would be no
understanding of it because there's been no wide debate on the issues,'' said
Francis Rolt, director of Studio Ijambo, an independent radio news and features
production unit in the Burundian capital, Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, Mandela invoked the recent past to warn of the perils of an
opaque negotiating process concluded under intense international pressure.
</P>
<P>
	   In April 6, 1994, in this same town, the extremist Hutu government of
neighboring Rwanda and a Tutsi rebel force reached a power-sharing agreement
ending a nearly 4-year-old war. ``That led to what we all know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The executive jet returning the Rwandan president home was shot from the sky
that night, killing him and igniting the genocide of at least 500,000 minority
Tutsis and politically moderate Hutus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 0212 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0023 </DOCNO>
