<DOCNO> APW20000221.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Light Shed on Kohl, Mitterrand  </HEADLINE>
   By CLAR NI CHONGHAILE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- In the early 1990s, Europe was an old continent moving toward
a new order with a seemingly unlikely alliance in the lead -- conservative
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany and Socialist President Francois Mitterrand of
France.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl and Mitterrand joined to guide the region in those unsure days after
the fall of communism, the link soldered by their visions for the future -- and
how they played and, according to recent allegations, financed politics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were not very democratic at heart. I think they had a very
interesting vision of Europe ... Europe was to be built from above,'' said
Anne-Marie Le Gloannec, deputy director of the Paris-based Center for
International Studies and Research.
</P>
<P>
	   Their relationship is under new scrutiny as part of a political party
financing scandal in Germany that has engulfed Kohl's Christian Democrats and is
chipping away at the reputation he earned as Germany's longest-serving
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
	   German and French television have reported that Mitterrand arranged for
payment of $15.7 million to Kohl's party in 1992 to help his friend's
re-election campaign. The reports said the money was part of $44 million in
payoffs made by French oil giant Elf Aquitaine for its 1992 purchase of a former
East German refinery at Leuna.
</P>
<P>
	   A German parliamentary committee investigating whether Kohl's government
took cash for political favors in the Leuna and other deals held its first
public hearing Thursday. The committee is trying to locate missing files
concerning the 1992 privatization of the Leuna refinery as well as the Minol gas
station chain while Kohl was still in office.
</P>
<P>
	   Elf Aquitaine, formerly a state-owned company, is the subject of a
meandering investigation into kickbacks in France.
</P>
<P>
	   The allegations about funneling money to Kohl's party have not been proven.
French Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou dismisses them as rumors, and Kohl's
spokesman says they are lies.
</P>
<P>
	   But the charges highlight the symbiosis that bound the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl's pet project was German reunification, while Mitterrand's was European
monetary union, and both needed each other for the success of their plans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For Mitterrand, Kohl was the guarantor of the realization of monetary
union. He was the only political figure in Germany who had the political force
necessary to impose it on the Germans,'' said Hans Stark of the French Institute
for International Relations.
</P>
<P>
	   In the early 1990s, the majority of Germans were not in favor of the
creation of a single currency, and many politicians said the project was a bad
idea.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl, in turn, needed France on his side if his ambitious plan to reunite
Germany was to succeed without reviving fears in a Europe that remembered the
Nazi regime of Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
	   Le Gloannec said Mitterrand initially opposed reunification. ``Kohl was more
daring. He could figure out that reunification would come, but he knew he had to
assuage French fears,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mitterrand finally accepted a single Germany, but that strengthened his
desire for political and monetary union in Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Mitterrand was a very conservative man in the sense that he had a vision
of Europe in which Europe should not change. But in spite of being conservative,
he very quickly understood he couldn't prevent reunification and that a unified
Germany had to be embedded in a unified Europe,'' Le Gloannec said.
</P>
<P>
	   As for the kind of politics practiced by the two men, they may have been
intent on securing the foundations of democracy in Europe, but their behavior
smacked of more autocratic impulses.
</P>
<P>
	   Le Gloannec describes them as ``Metternich-like'' leaders -- a reference to
Prince Klemens von Metternich of Austria who helped redraw the borders of Europe
after the Napoleonic Wars.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite their shared goals, Mitterrand and Kohl were not imitations of one
another.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Mitterrand was the prototype of the French intellectual, very literary;
Kohl was more coarse and simple, a pure politician,'' said Olivier Duhamel, a
Socialist member of the European Parliament and a professor of politics at the
Sorbonne.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But they were both great Machiavellian opportunists who would do anything
for power, and the one constant for them was Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
