<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Mayor Seeks Civil Bogota  </HEADLINE>
   By JARED KOTLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Sidewalks don't typically stir passions, but they
do for Mayor Enrique Penalosa, even if it means risking his job.
</P>
<P>
	   Penalosa faced a serious impeachment drive last year just for trying to stop
people from parking their cars on sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
	   Now he has some people angry over a plan to turn a posh golf and polo club
into a park and a one-day ban on cars he's ordered for this Thursday -- to
demonstrate how much better Bogota would be without them.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor's crusades are about more than just scofflaw parking or reducing
traffic and pollution. They symbolize what has become the goal of government in
one of Latin America's least-loved capitals: improving life by challenging
residents to put the common good ahead of themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   By trying to foster a sense of community, Penalosa hopes not just to soften
life's edges in Bogota, but to offer an example for other cities that aspire to
more than simply coping with the burdens of growth.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While the country urbanized quickly during the past 50 years, we learned
to survive, to build water mains, sewers, to open a lot of schools, to provide
electricity,'' Penalosa said in a recent interview. ``The challenge now is to
learn not to survive, but to live.''
</P>
<P>
	   One expert on Bogota's development puts it more bluntly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The problem is no longer that there aren't any public telephones; it's to
get people to stop breaking them,'' said Fabio Zambrano, a historian at the
National University.
</P>
<P>
	   Bogota's experiments in civics -- Penalosa's predecessor deployed mimes to
shame the city's notoriously aggressive drivers -- might be the only path to
happiness for a metropolis lacking other obvious attractions.
</P>
<P>
	   Sprawled on a chilly, rain-soaked plateau at 8,500 feet above sea level, and
with a spine of mountains brooding over its eastern edge, Colombia's capital has
always been a spartan place.
</P>
<P>
	   Bogota's population has soared tenfold to 7 million over the past five
decades, ballooned by poor people flooding in from the countryside.
</P>
<P>
	   A huge increase in car ownership has created some of Latin America's worst
traffic jams, which are exacerbated by widespread flouting of traffic laws. Even
the shortest drive can be a frightening odyssey among smog-belching buses
swerving wildly to unload passengers or beat the competition to a fare.
</P>
<P>
	   Adding to the unpleasantness are Bogota's frequent hailstorms and average
annual rainfall of 37 inches, compared to famously drizzly London's 23 or
Seattle's 33.
</P>
<P>
	   Given the city's foul weather, infuriating traffic and unremarkable
architecture, Bogota's recent leaders have tried to at least build community
spirit.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Although it's not a city that the people care for very much, it has its
attractions,'' said Antanas Mockus, Penalosa's predecessor. ``It's a laboratory
for quickly changing the way people live together.''
</P>
<P>
	   It was Mockus who posted mimes at stoplights to teach civility. He
instituted a late-night bar-closing law that reduced homicides, and he got
residents to save water by taking shorter showers.
</P>
<P>
	   Penalosa, a Duke University graduate with a doctorate from France, has
carried out traditional projects like patching roads and opening parks. And this
year, his last in office, he plans to begin a public bus system over fierce
opposition from the powerful private bus companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Penalosa is most passionate, however, about the misuse of sidewalks, the
dispute that threatened his job.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sidewalks are for children to play on, for couples to seduce, for old men
to sit down and read the newspaper and discuss politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   That's why he ordered city workers to install hundreds of concrete barriers
along curbs last year, making it impossible for drivers to park their cars on
sidewalks. An impeachment campaign sprang up from irate motorists and angry
shopkeepers, who had turned miles of pedestrian walkways into clogged private
parking bays.
</P>
<P>
	   He fended off the critics, though, and opinion polls say his popularity is
rising. He earned 1999 man-of-the-year honors from Colombia's top two news
magazines.
</P>
<P>
	   To broad applause, the mayor recently reopened one of Bogota's most
deteriorated shopping districts with wide, clean walkways and not a car on the
sidewalk. He also has restricted car use during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
	   Perhaps one of his stranger projects -- considering the weather -- is to
build 180 miles of bike paths that he says will encourage people to pedal to
work. ``Cars isolate people,'' he said. ``Bicycles integrate socially.''
</P>
<P>
	   Even if anti-social tendencies still abound, there are signs civility is
taking root. Crowds of rich and poor mingle peacefully every Sunday on the
``Ciclovia,'' a circuit of streets closed off to cars all morning.
</P>
<P>
	   An estimated 1.4 million Bogotanos -- bicyclists, joggers, in-line skaters
and dog walkers -- take to the outdoors each weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Some even swear the weather has improved.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Those of us who grew up in Bogota are convinced it's raining less,'' said
Mockus, the former mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
