<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Tap Water Not Created Equal  </HEADLINE>
   By VICKI SMITH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- All tap water is not created equal.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, after sipping thousands of samples from all over the world, Arthur
von Wiesenberger knows this much: The shorter the journey from source to spigot,
the more pleasing it will be to the palate.
</P>
<P>
	   Von Wiesenberger, a California author and trained ``water master,'' will
help pick the best this weekend at the International Water Tasting in Berkeley
Springs, W.Va., the largest competition of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10-year-old contest, which features water from more than two dozen
states and four countries, is expanding almost as rapidly as the $4.8 billion
bottled-water industry, which grows about 10 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's bigger than ever. There's nothing else quite like it,'' says
Wiesenberger, who will train amateur judges to gauge water in three categories
-- municipal, bottled non-carbonated and bottled sparkling.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's no other place for municipalities to compare their waters in a
non-biased environment,'' von Wiesenberger says from Santa Barbara, Calif. ``The
chance to be recognized ... is like winning the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
	   Literally. There are big payoffs for commercial winners, who can proclaim
their victories on their bottle labels and increase sales.
</P>
<P>
	   For municipal competitors, though, it boils down to bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have tasted a lot of municipal water and I honestly feel none of it
compares to Mount Airy's water,'' says Gerald Johnson, a mayor from Maryland,
the home state of Mount Airy.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of course, others might disagree,'' Johnson concedes.
</P>
<P>
	   Clearly, Mount Airy, Md., has competition: Among this year's entrants are
three-time winner Atlantic City, N.J., and two-time winner Charleston, W.Va.
Also back in the municipal category is last year's winner, Desert Hot Springs,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What's really fascinating is the results, no matter who the judges are --
and the judges change every year,'' von Wiesenberger says. ``There's a certain
concentration of minerals that keeps coming up.''
</P>
<P>
	   Atlantic City may not win every year, but it consistently finishes in the
top five or 10, apparently using either a good filtration system or tapping into
a great source.
</P>
<P>
	   And Desert Hot Springs' victory last year ``flies in the face of assumptions
that southern California has bad water,'' von Wiesenberger says. It relies on a
pristine source, supporting the notion that the more natural a water is, the
better it will taste.
</P>
<P>
	   Other municipal water systems use as many as 30 chemicals to clarify and
flavor their water. They generally don't fare as well in competition.
</P>
<P>
	   To keep their senses sharp, the judges are forbidden to smoke, drink coffee
or alcohol, eat spicy food or chew gum within a half-hour of the contest. Like
wine-tasters, they will tap into senses of sight, smell and taste.
</P>
<P>
	   They hold clean, clear, hand-buffed glasses to the light and inspect the
water for clarity. Points are deducted for things like cloudiness and
discoloration.
</P>
<P>
	   Then the judges sniff, hoping not to smell sulfur, chlorine, mustiness or
swampiness.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One judge described one entry as smelling like guppy water,'' von
Wiesenberger recalls. ``Sure enough, it came from a source that had fish in
it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Finally, they roll the water around the mouth, looking for a metallic or
chemical taste as well as saltiness, sweetness or bitterness. Ideally, none of
those should exist.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But you're not looking for the absence of everything,'' von Wiesenberger
explains. ``If you wanted that, you could drink distilled water. But distilled
water leaves your palate tasting flat or dull. You want minerals, but you want a
certain combination.''
</P>
<P>
	   Potassium, for example, makes it sweeter; calcium and magnesium give it
fullness.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm always fascinated to see how some of the returnees do,'' von
Wiesenberger says. Even perennial losers return year after year, often having
modified their processing to reflect the judges' comments.
</P>
<P>
	   And the contest likely will continue to grow. There are more than 900
commercial water bottlers in the United States, von Wiesenberger says, ``so
there's a lot of room for growth.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But there are also those that would never want to enter because they know
they wouldn't fare well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
