<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Denies Report of Defection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea on Monday denied a newspaper report
that a missile expert from communist North Korea had defected to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
	   Quoting unidentified Chinese sources, Chosun Ilbo, South Korea's largest
daily newspaper, reported last week that Im Ki Song, 59, a North Korean missile
expert, defected to the United States via China in January, along with two
relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Chosun Ilbo article on the defection of a North Korean missile expert
is groundless,'' the Foreign Affairs Ministry said in a one-sentence statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The national Yonhap news agency, quoting an unidentified ministry official,
said South Korea had checked with the United States on the reported defection
and was told it was false.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Embassy in Seoul could not be reached for comment because it was
closed Monday for Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   North Korea's missile capability has become a matter of worldwide concern
since the isolated country fired a three-stage rocket in 1998 that flew over
Japan and landed in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
	   After negotiations with the United States last September, North Korea agreed
to forgo further missile tests during the duration of talks with Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   But the North is threatening to resume missile tests, complaining that the
United States is unwilling to drop its hostile policy toward the hard-line
communist regime.
</P>
<P>
	   North Korea recently agreed to send a high-ranking official to Washington in
March to discuss ways of improving ties.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States fought against North Korea on South Korea's side in the
1950-53 Korean War. About 37,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South Korea under
a defense treaty.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 450 North Koreans have defected to South Korea since 1994, about
one-third of them in 1999. Many complained of hunger in their homeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 0309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China General To Streamline Forces  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE (AP) -- The head of China's air force said Monday his country will
streamline its huge military, and promised that Beijing would never ``invade or
threaten any sovereign state.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Gen. Liu Shunyao was addressing high-level participants from around the
world who were taking part in a Millennium Air Power Conference in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
	   Liu said the Chinese would aim at ``winning local wars directed against
China under high-tech conditions on short notice.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'll stick to the road of streamlining the armed forces the Chinese
way,'' the air force commander said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that would include better weapons, military theories and training to
achieve the ``goal of defense plus offense.''
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the strong words, Liu also promised: ``China will never invade or
threaten any sovereign state. But it will definitely not allow any other country
to invade China.''
</P>
<P>
	   Liu has already urged rapid military modernization aimed at turning its 2.7
million-member army -- rooted in guerrilla warfare -- into a modern fighting
force armed with weapons to rival those of the United States and other Western
powers.
</P>
<P>
	   Chinese anxieties have been fueled by the Persian Gulf War and NATO's war
against Yugoslavia, where Western forces used laser-guided bombs and other
weapons that China lacks.
</P>
<P>
	   China has poured tens of billions of dollars into upgrading its arsenal in
recent years, buying supersonic Russian fighter planes and developing cruise and
ballistic missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 0311 </TRAILER>
