<HEADLINE> S. Korean Officials To Visit U.S.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korean military officials will visit the
United States this week as part of an investigation into an alleged mass killing
of civilian refugees by U.S. troops during the Korean War, the Defense Ministry
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Gen. Kim Jong-hwan, assistant defense minister for policy and planning,
will lead the six-member team, which will arrive Tuesday in Washington for a
five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
	   The trip will mark the third meeting between military investigators from
both countries who are investigating the killings at No Gun Ri village. The last
meeting was held in mid-January when U.S. Army Secretary Louis Caldera visited
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
	   The two sides plan to discuss progress in their investigations, share
information and jointly interview some of the U.S. veterans who were allegedly
involved in the case, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing dozens of villagers and U.S. veterans, The Associated Press reported
in September that hundreds of Korean civilians were killed by American soldiers
at No Gun Ri in central South Korea in July 1950.
</P>
<P>
	   According to declassified U.S. military documents, American ground
commanders feared that North Korean soldiers, dressed in civilian clothes, were
infiltrating refugee columns.
</P>
<P>
	   The governments of the United States and South Korea previously dismissed
the claims, but opened investigations after the AP report was published.
</P>
<P>
	   In the 1950-53 Korean War, the United States led a 16-nation U.N. force in
the defense of South Korea against an invasion by North Korea, which was backed
by China and the Soviet Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
