<HEADLINE> Cast members and fans come to terms with impending close of 'Cats'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The mood was somber yet nostalgic as the news sunk in
with cast members and fans alike that "Cats," the longest-running show in
Broadway history, will close in June after a record-breaking 7,397 performances.
<P>
	   "When we got the news there were tears, sure, and hugs. And believe it or
not there was lots of laughter. Somehow everybody knows in their heart that
nothing goes forever," said Marlene Danielle, who has played the feline
character Bombalurina since the show started in October 1982. "We brought the
show into the new millennium. How much more can you really expect?"
</P>
<P>
	   The musical, which has a score by Andrew Lloyd Webber, will bring down the
curtain June 25, after a nearly two-decade run at Broadway's Winter Garden
Theater.
</P>
<P>
	   "Cats," which is advertised as "Now and Forever" and has long been a major
tourist attraction, will have been seen by more than 10 million theatergoers in
New York by the end of the run.
</P>
<P>
	   The show's grosses on Broadway alone are estimated to be more than $380
million. Yet in the last two years, its weekly receipts have been dwindling, at
times falling to only 50 percent capacity, particularly in the lean winter
months after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was bound to happen someday. When you look at it, we're running into our
18th year and the houses have been slow. It's a business, and they have to make
their money," Danielle said.
</P>
<P>
	   Although cast members admitted to being sad and disappointed, they said that
knowing the end is near makes the remaining performances even more special.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's really very exciting to be a member of the last cast," said Lenny
Daniel, 33, who plays the character Alonzo.
</P>
<P>
	   Fans of the show were saddened by the news but also expressed a feeling of
nostalgia upon learning that the show would not really be "Now and Forever."
</P>
<P>
	   "When I first heard the news I was devastated," said uber-fan Hector
Montalvo, a Manhattan computer software salesman who said he has seen the show
670 times. "This is such a sad thing, but I guess all good things must come to
an end."
</P>
<P>
	   Montalvo, tears streaming down his face, waited in line for Sunday's
matinee.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the 10th time I have seen it, and I must admit I'm feeling pretty
sad," said Ernie Puglise, a music teacher from Connecticut who took his classes
many times over the years to see the show. "I really think it's the best musical
ever written."
</P>
<P>
	   Both performers and fans, however, admitted that despite the show's
impending closing they were optimistic about the future.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've all been auditioning for other things because we knew this had to
happen at some point," said Tesha Bess, who has played the character Rumple
Teaser for the last 1 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Montalvo, the fan, said that although he was upset he knew that life would
go on.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've made friends with a lot of the cast and I look forward to seeing them
in their future projects," he said with a smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 0550 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 05:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran's death recalls Navy record - six brothers who served at  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Eager hands motivated by empty stomachs reached out
toward the parked car with its rumble seat full of sacks leaking dirt.
<P>
	   In the midst of the small crowd stood a contingent of the Martin boys. The
teen-agers handed out potatoes from the heaping bags - a bounty brought back to
their neighborhood in Flushing, Queens, from an overnight excursion to dig up
potatoes that otherwise would go unharvested on Long Island farms.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the 1930s, the Great Depression. Everyone was poor, and everyone was
familiar with hunger. The potatoes meant a sure meal.
</P>
<P>
	   The Martin boys were known for banding together to help out. That's why no
one was surprised when a few years later six of the brothers joined the Navy in
World War II, even though no six sons from one family ever served in the Navy at
one time - before or since
</P>
<P>
	   The boys got their spirit from their dad, who toiled at two jobs to feed a
family of 13, brought starving families home to dinner, and once paid an
out-of-work bricklayer to repair the family fireplace - which was not really
broken - in hopes it would restore the man's pride.
</P>
<P>
	   Like their dad, the boys believed in family - theirs was seven brothers,
three sisters, their parents and an uncle - and in community, in an age when
many city neighborhoods were as caring as small towns. That's why the neighbors
found it natural when most of the Martin sons went off to World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   "Nobody questioned it," recalled sister Agnes Martin. "Nobody thought it was
anything outstanding. It was always what people did."
</P>
<P>
	   Each time a Martin walked into the recruitment office, their mother grabbed
needle and thread and added another gold star to the navy blue flag at the front
window. The six stars represented her boys: John Jr., Edward, William, James,
Charles and Robert.
</P>
<P>
	   All survived the war, and now this unusual chapter in the U.S. military's
history has closed. Charles, the last remaining brother, died late last month
following a lengthy illness at age 81.
</P>
<P>
	   Military historians doubt one family will ever contribute so many sons again
to a war. That is due partly to today's smaller families. In 1930, a U.S family
averaged 4.1 people, and it was not unusual for a couple to have a half-dozen
sons. Today, the average family size is about 2.5.
</P>
<P>
	   "Just finding six brothers of military age, well, I guess you could, but it
wouldn't be probable," said Jerry Cooper, a professor of U.S. military history
at the University of Missouri-St. Louis. "You can say the differences are more
demography and social change, rather than anything to do with the military."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the military has changed. The country is not at war, the draft is
gone, and the military has downsized. Most expansion is focused on technology,
not numbers. And as on expert explained, the appeal for volunteering has faded,
too.
</P>
<P>
	   "In those days, it seemed like a respectable thing to do," said Charles
Moskos, a professor of military sociology at Northwestern University in
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
	   But Moskos said this doesn't mean the military has no family connections.
"Husbands and wives serving together - that's the new military," Moskos said.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that women make up 15 percent of the armed forces and estimated
that 50 percent of them are married to servicemen.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Martins, little made their story special beyond the number of
brothers. Yes, they all fought, even participating in every World War II theater
involving U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
	   But their sacrifice pales when compared with that of the Sullivans, five
brothers all killed serving together on a cruiser sunk by a Japanese torpedo in
1942. When the news hit the states, a horrified Congress approved the "Sullivan
Act" forbidding siblings from serving on the same ship.
</P>
<P>
	   A few of the Martin boys had served together at one time or another, but
never all on the same ship. Early in the war, Mrs. Martin urged daughter Agnes
to write a letter asking President Roosevelt to put the boys together.
</P>
<P>
	   She came to Agnes in a panic when the Sullivans were killed and was relieved
to learn her daughter had put off the letter since some of the boys didn't like
the idea of saluting one brother who had been promoted.
</P>
<P>
	   "My mother was crying and on her knees, praying in gratitude," Agnes Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
	   So the Martins' story wasn't "Saving Private Ryan" - the recent film about
World War II that capitalized on the notion of a country not only sending
brothers-in-arms, but real brothers, into battle together.
</P>
<P>
	   What the Martins did was serve their country, supporting the Allies'
victory. James Forestall, then Secretary of the Navy, sent the family a letter
lauding the sons' patriotism.
</P>
<P>
	   After the war, the brothers came home, started families, and began spreading
throughout the New York area. William returned to Japan to marry a woman he had
met. Each got a job, frequently utilizing technical skills.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles became a cook in Brooklyn and later, like some of his brothers, an
airline engineer. After retiring, he volunteered at the Brooklyn School for
Special Children, where one of his son's had been educated.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the Martins talked little about their service during the war, their
children knew they never forgot it.
</P>
<P>
	   "They were damn proud of it, too - not of the six thing - but that they did
their duty," said Elizabeth Egan, Charles Martin's daughter. "They felt it was
their obligation as United States citizens to do that."
</P>
<P>
	   For at least one of the brothers, it came close to never happening. Robert -
the smallest of an already diminutive brood - needed the help of his sisters to
make the weight to enlist. To add some pounds, they mixed a concoction of eggs,
heavy cream and beer for him to drink before the weigh-in. But that wasn't
enough, and it took a well-timed foot on the scale from an older brother for
Robert to be accepted.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond the desire to serve the country, there was at least one other reason
the boys enlisted. Their Uncle James had been an army man who served in five
wars. When he retired, he moved in with the family and his pension helped pay
some bills. So the boys grew up hearing James' war stories.
</P>
<P>
	   The tales must have had some impact. But Agnes Martin recalled something
else that played an important role. Mrs. Martin was a talented seamstress who
made her first sons sailor suits when they were little, and these later were
passed on to brothers.
</P>
<P>
	   "We always thought it was so ironic," Agnes Martin said. "It was almost a
premonition."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 0550 </TRAILER>
