<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Stock Markets End Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock closed sharply lower Monday on the back
of last week's tumble on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 245.28 points, or
1.23 percent, to finish the day at 19,543.75 points. On Friday, the average
closed down 2.37 points, or 0.01 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nikkei average fell on fears the U.S. economy could slow with future
interest rate hikes. A weaker U.S. economy would hurt Japanese companies that
sell products there.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 295.05 points, or 2.8
percent, to close at 10,219.52 on Friday. The tech-laden Nasdaq composite index
fell 137.18 points to 4,411.74.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's losses were cushioned by a sharp rise in shares of Sony Corp.,
whose PlayStation2 game console is expected to meet with strong demand when it
goes on sale March 4.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 110.58 yen, down 0.16 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 110.96 yen
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korean shares plunged, with the key index falling 3.8 percent in
reaction to the sharp fall on Wall Street. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index
fell 33.82 points 845.32.
</P>
<P>
	   In Hong Kong, the blue chip Hang Seng Index fell 276.79 points, or 1.7
percent, to close at 16,322.37. On Friday, the index had tumbled 382.07 points,
or 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are worried about further increases in U.S. interest rates
following a warning last week by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
that such action may be needed to keep U.S. inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
	   The market was closed in Thailand for a holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
	   SINGAPORE: Singaporean share prices closed lower following Wall Street's
fall and on weak regional sentiment. The benchmark Straits Times Index fell
61.51 points, or 2.8 percent, to 2,115.85.
</P>
<P>
	   MANILA: Philippine shares slumped, dragged down by heavy foreign selling
after Wall Street's huge loss and the ongoing probe into trading irregularities
involving shares of gaming group BW Resources Corp. The 30-company Philippine
Stock Exchange Index fell 50.44 points, or 2.7 percent, to 18,33.84.
</P>
<P>
	   TAIPEI: Taiwan shares closed lower as investors rushed to sell technology
stocks after Nasdaq's 3 percent fall Friday. The Weighted Stock Price Index fell
248.38 points, or 2.4 percent, to 9,912.67.
</P>
<P>
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed little changed. The NZSE-40
Capital Index edged up 0.63 point tp 2,031.85.
</P>
<P>
	   SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed slightly lower in thin trading as
many investors sat on the sidelines with the U.S. closed for a public holiday on
Monday. The All Ordinaries Index closed at 3,117.1, down 3.0 points, or 0.09.
</P>
<P>
	   KUALA LUMPUR: The key index fell on profit-taking. The Composite Index,
which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, closed at 1,007.13 points, down 6.14 points
or 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   JAKARTA: Indonesian shares continued their slide Monday. The Composite Index
fell 6.585 points, or 1.1 percent, to 592.988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
