<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Defends New Market Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong in
Parliament Monday defended the government's recent easing of stock exchange
rules. He was responding to questions about the dangers of high-risk Internet
stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   The recently loosened rules were necessary to enable capital markets to fund
a new economy based on high-tech and knowledge-based industries, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Otherwise either high-tech companies will be choked off from equity
capital, or they will list overseas, for example, on Nasdaq, and our stock
market will wither," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
	   Lee was responding to questions from legislator Wang Kai Yuen, who expressed
concerns in Parliament about how Singaporeans "can participate in the Internet
boom without being sucked into the asset bubble."
</P>
<P>
	   Wang suggested that the government "express stronger words of caution
regarding new IPOs (initial public offerings) of dot.com companies," he said,
comparing this to "the practice of printing warnings on packs of cigarettes."
</P>
<P>
	   Lee acknowledged that there were risks involved in some high-tech stocks,
but said Singaporean investors could educate themselves and make informed
decisions.
</P>
<P>
	   "Risk taking is the essence of the new economy," he said. "But we will
educate the public in the risks, so that people know what they are doing, and do
it with their eyes open."
</P>
<P>
	   Since the recent change in rules, five companies have been listed that
wouldn't have qualified under the old rules.
</P>
<P>
	   They are MediaRing.com, Horizon.com, ST Assembly Test Services Ltd.,
Chartered Semiconductor Manufacturing Ltd., and China Toll Bridges and Roads
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
	   Lee said the new listing rules and the philosophy behind it are sound.
</P>
<P>
	   "The government cannot stop companies from being listed on the Singapore
Exchange because it thinks their business is too risky, or their shares are
priced too high," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that what the government can do is to enforce the rules of the
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1022 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Havas Advertising Buys Snyder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    PARIS (AP) -- France's Havas Advertising SA confirmed Monday that it has
bought Snyder Communications Inc. in a stock deal worth $2.07 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The move makes Havas the world's fourth largest advertising concern, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
	   The new group will have a market capitalization of $6.42 billion and annual
revenues of more than $19 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Havas' chairman, Alain de Pouzilhac, said in a statement that the Snyder
deal gave the French group a chance to step up its North American presence.
</P>
<P>
	   The acquisition will nearly double its revenues from the United States,
boosting them from 30 percent to 45 percent of overall sales.
</P>
<P>
	   The French company said the new group formed after the absorption of
Bethesda, Md.-based Snyder will be 70 percent controlled by current Havas
shareholders and 30 percent by Snyder.
</P>
<P>
	   Half the new group's clients will be in telecommunications, technology,
financial services, media and healthcare, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Havas' largest shareholder -- French giant Vivendi SA -- is likely to see
its stake in the advertising group diluted to 14.5 percent from its current 20.7
percent as a result of the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement has now been submitted for approval by both regulatory
authorities and the two groups' shareholders.
</P>
<P>
	   Both boards have already given their go-ahead, and Havas says it expects the
transaction to be closed by mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
	   The Snyder group comprises four separate advertising and marketing agencies:
Arnold Communications, Bounty SCA Worldwide, Brann Worldwide and Circle.com.
</P>
<P>
	   Snyder shareholders will receive $29.50 per share, representing Havas
Advertising common shares, which will be registered with the Securities &AMP;
Exchange Commission and listed in the United States once the deal is sealed.
</P>
<P>
	   The new group will be the world's fourth largest advertising concern behind
U.S. groups Omnicom and Interpublic and Britain's WPP, Havas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1033 </TRAILER>
