<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CGU, Norwich Union Plan Merger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- Insurance companies CGU PLC and Norwich Union PLC are
combining in a $12 billion stock deal that will form Britain's biggest insurance
group.
</P>
<P>
	   The new company, to be called CGNU, would have a market value of about $30
billion. It would be the largest provider of general insurance and the
second-largest provider of life insurance in Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies said today that 5,000 jobs or 7 percent of their total work
force, will be cut as part of the combination. Shareholders of the two companies
and British financial authorities still must approve the all-share transaction.
</P>
<P>
	   The new company, which would be called CGNU, would be Europe's fifth-biggest
insurer and be based in London.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal would give the combined company strong positions in several
European and international markets, said CGU chief executive Bob Scott, who is
to continue in the same role at the new group.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the deal, CGU shareholders would control 58.5 percent of the new
group, while Norwich Union shareholders would control 41.5 percent of the group.
CGU would appoint nine of the group's 17 directors.
</P>
<P>
	   A wave of consolidation has swept Britain's insurance and financial services
sectors. Royal Bank of Scotland won a $33.6 billion takeover bid for National
Westminster earlier this month, while Lloyds TSB acquired the insurance group
Scottish Widows last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
