<HEADLINE> Sithe Sells 21 Plants to Reliant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HOUSTON (AP) -- Reliant Energy is buying 21 power plants from Sithe
Energies, a privately held electricity producer whose generators dot the Middle
Atlantic region, for $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal gives Houston-based Reliant a major foothold in one of five regions
the company is targeting as it expands its unregulated power generating
capacity. Sixteen of the plants Reliant is acquiring from Sithe Energies are in
Pennsylvania, with four in New Jersey and one in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale is expected to be finalized by midyear.
</P>
<P>
	   "These newly acquired assets, which will be managed closely with Reliant's
trading, origination and development activities in the region, will position us
well to pursue follow-on opportunities to control additional generation and
serve complex customer needs," said Joe Bob Perkins, president of Reliant Energy
Wholesale group.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal also includes 18 sites Reliant could use to expand or build new
power plants that are adjacent to or near the existing power plants.
</P>
<P>
	   New York-based Sithe is one of the largest power producers in the United
States. It is owned 60 percent by the French water and utilities giant Vivendi,
29 percent by the Japanese trading firm Marubeni and 11 percent by its two
cofounders.
</P>
<P>
	   A Vivendi spokesman said the sale was made in part because of the high costs
necessary to compete in the quickly deregulating U.S. energy market.
</P>
<P>
	   Vivendi has been concentrating on the services side of the energy business
through its Paris-based Dalkia unit, which manages heating networks and other
facilities. Synergies between the European unit and the U.S. one were few and
far between, Vivendi officials said. The energy unit also was dwarfed by
Vivendi's telecommunications investments.
</P>
<P>
	   "U.S. deregulation of the business was such that it needed considerable
capital to grow," said Vivendi spokesman Alain Delrieux. "When we did our
strategic review six months ago, we saw that synergies (with Dalkia) were
relatively weak because they weren't the same businesses. ... Was Vivendi, given
those synergies, ready to pour in a lot of capital? That was the issue and we'd
decided to invest elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
	   Sithe and Vivendi also announced the formation of K Road Ventures, an
Internet energy company focused on business-to-business ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
