<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Language Heroes Honored  </HEADLINE>
   By FARID HOSSAIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- Nearly 100,000 barefooted people converged on a
monument Monday to pay tribute to five Bangladeshi students who were shot and
killed by police nearly five decades ago during a protest over the suppression
of the national language.
</P>
<P>
	   On Feb. 21, 1952, university students revolted when the Pakistani rulers
declared Urdu the only official language, although people of Bangladesh -- at
that time the eastern wing of Pakistan -- speak Bangla. Bangladesh won
independence from Pakistan in 1971.
</P>
<P>
	   Braving chilly winds, men, women and children -- who wore no shoes or socks
as a mark of respect -- waited in long lines to place wreathes at the monument
in central Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
	   Many came from nearby towns and villages. Dozens also came from neighboring
India, traveling from West Bengal state where Bangla is also spoken.
</P>
<P>
	   The ceremonies began with President Shahabuddin Ahmed, Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina and opposition leader Khaleda Zia placing wreathes studded with marigolds
and roses at the monument -- three curved stone pillars in the form of a bowing
human being.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've been standing in the line for two hours and this is worth the
occasion,'' said Sharmina Nargis, a Dhaka University student.
</P>
<P>
	   During the 1952 protests, thousands of students took to the streets,
demanding that both Urdu and Bangla be recognized as official languages. Police
cracked down on the protesters, killing five.
</P>
<P>
	   Since then, Bangladeshis have observed Feb. 21 as Language Day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This was the day when we realized that we will have to gain our
independence,'' said Abdul Matin, who participated in the 1952 protest as a
student.
</P>
<P>
	   Bangladesh successfully proposed last year to the United Nations that Feb.
21 be deemed International Mother Language Day. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan issued a message published by Dhaka newspapers commemorating the event.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This day will help raise awareness among all peoples about the distinct
and enduring value of their languages,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
	   The language celebrations in Bangladesh focus on literary and cultural
achievements, and include book fairs and awards for writers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1225 </TRAILER>
