<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill would lift ban on Sunday deer hunting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Deer populations are exploding across New Jersey,
and now officials are thinking about lifting the state's 97-year-old ban on
Sunday hunting.
<P>
	   While some towns retain "blue laws" prohibiting shopping or car sales on
Sunday, the ban on hunting is one of the few Sunday laws that still applies
across the state.
</P>
<P>
	   But Sen. William Schluter, R-Mercer, said it is time to revisit the law
because deer now pose an epidemic problem for farmers and motorists.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey Division of Fish &AMP; Wildlife Director Bob McDowell says the deer
hunting ban has always seemed inconsistent since other shooting sports are
permitted on Sundays and fishing has always been allowed.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bottom line is that a lot of hunters don't have the time to get out in
the woods anymore," McDowell told The Record of Hackensack for Monday's
editions. "Now they might have the chance to enjoy themselves and thin the deer
herd at the same time."
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's 2000-2001 deer hunting season will run from mid-September
through January. Farmers who sustain crop damage are eligible for special 30-day
licenses at other times of the year, but even they are prohibited from shooting
deer on Sunday. An estimated 100,000 people are currently licensed to hunt in
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate Economic Growth and Agriculture committee last week approved the
Schluter bill, S-810, sending it to the full Senate for consideration. It would
only apply to counties with rural areas and it would permit local town councils
to choose for themselves whether or not to maintain the Sunday ban.
</P>
<P>
	   Schluter told the newspaper he believes most towns in his legislative
district would jump to permit Sunday hunting. Although he lives in a Mercer
County suburb, his district covers all of Hunterdon County and rural parts of
Warren County. Figures show deer have made travel on rural roads increasingly
hazardous, especially at night, and farmers have increased their complaints
about crop damage from deer forage.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's an extreme measure, but these are extreme times," Schluter said. "The
deer must be stopped."
</P>
<P>
	   McDowell said, "There are a lot of farmers out there that really need help."
</P>
<P>
	   The Sunday hunting bill is one of several deer-control measures being
pursued by lawmakers who represent rural areas. One bill would revamp the
state's carcass pickup program, which is struggling to keep pace with the road
kill, while another bill would set up a system to process deer meat for donation
to the state's needy.
</P>
<P>
	   But those who oppose deer hunting as a means of controlling the population
believe the expansion of hunting is not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
	   Pat McElroy, a wildlife researcher at the Humane Society of the United
States in Washington, said clearing the way for Sunday hunting is not worth the
trade-off for the majority of residents who may want to enjoy at least one day
outdoors without the danger of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
	   "Why make our woods less safe for the tiny minority of people who want to
hunt?" McElroy said.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials say more than 15,000 deer were found dead or dying on New
Jersey highways in 1998, almost twice the number found just a decade ago.
According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, more than a
quarter-million highway accidents in 1997 involved animals, mostly deer,
including 142 fatal accidents nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   Farmers, meanwhile, said the simultaneous growth in deer population and
suburban housing tracts has concentrated deer onto the remaining farm acres.
</P>
<P>
	   "I say bring the hunters on Saturday, Sunday, every day," said Delaware
Township farmer Ken Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 1354 </TRAILER>
