<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former TV Producer Tries Teaching  </HEADLINE>
    By DOUG JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOPLIN, Mo. (AP) -- Smoke billowed from gutted buildings near Joanne
Brough's home. Student protesters rioted in the streets. The Indonesian economy
was teetering, and rioters in Jakarta were demanding a change of leadership.
</P>
<P>
	   Brough and her husband, Charles, an American couple caught in the middle of
a fight they barely understood, were forced to flee, leaving their possessions
behind.
</P>
<P>
	   The former producer and developer of prime-time soap operas like "Falcon
Crest" and "Dallas" was used to drama and intrigue, but she never counted on
getting caught up in a real national crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   She was working for two years in Jakarta helping produce a locally grown
soap.
</P>
<P>
	   "Towards the end, there were armed guards in the studio and barbed wire
around everything," Brough says. "I wanted a little adventure. I got more than I
expected."
</P>
<P>
	   A year and a half later, the 71-year-old Brough has landed back in her
hometown of Joplin -- a quiet nook in southwest Missouri that offers a lifestyle
"just right for someone who had to escape a revolution."
</P>
<P>
	   Semi-retired now, Brough is on to Act Two of her life, teaching a television
script-writing course twice a week at Missouri Southern State College.
</P>
<P>
	   "Does anyone know what a cliffhanger is?" she asked her students during one
recent class as she loads a "Falcon Crest" rerun into the VCR.
</P>
<P>
	   In the clip, the vineyards of the show's California valley have fallen
victim to an earthquake. A woman rushes around her house calling out for her
fiance, then finds him dead on the floor.
</P>
<P>
	   "It doesn't hurt if you have a cliffhanger at the end of every scene,"
Brough explains.
</P>
<P>
	   Her students hang on her every word. Most of them realize by now that
Brough's resume reads like a page from TV Guide: For most of the 1960s and '70s,
she oversaw the development of series like "Kojak," "Hawaii Five-O," "All in the
Family," "M A S H," "Dallas" and the "Mary Tyler Moore Show" at CBS.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1978, she moved over to Lorimar Productions and became vice president of
creative affairs for all on-air programs, and in 1986 was promoted to executive
producer of "Falcon Crest," where she stayed for four years.
</P>
<P>
	   For a woman who spent nearly half her life running a piece of Hollywood,
Brough is amazingly humble, but not without confidence -- a strange mix of your
favorite aunt and "Falcon Crest" matriarch Angela Channing.
</P>
<P>
	   One minute she'll tell you about a shrewd business lunch with foreign TV
executives, and the next laugh about the time she was convinced her dentist had
given her a truth serum anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
	   "I only knew one secret, and when I came to I found myself saying to the
dentist, 'Would you like to know who shot J.R.?"' she says, shaking her head. "I
guess the pressure was a little too much."
</P>
<P>
	   She also likes chatting about the hundreds of TV personalities she hired and
worked with.
</P>
<P>
	   Jane Wyman (Angela Channing) was one of her favorites.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I was working I tried to keep relationships on a professional level.
But in the case of Jane, we just got to be great friends," she says.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1991, Brough traveled to Rome to film "Killer Rules," a two-hour TV movie
about the mafia. She then spent three years in Singapore developing "Masters of
the Sea," the first English-language drama on Asian television.
</P>
<P>
	   Her biggest challenge came in 1996 when Indonesia's No. 1 network, RCTI,
asked Brough to create from scratch an in-house drama department.
</P>
<P>
	   She was to produce a local soap opera along the lines of "Dallas." So she
set to work on "Dua Sisi Mata Uang" (Two Sides of the Coin) -- a
J.R.-Ewing-meets-the-Waltons brand of show.
</P>
<P>
	   Americans might not have recognized it as a soap: Local customs meant no
kissing on screen, and the budget was a mere $42,000 per episode, compared to
about $1 million for "Dallas" and "Falcon Crest."
</P>
<P>
	   Brough managed to film 26 episodes before the civil unrest in 1998 forced
her to evacuate. She and her husband moved back to Joplin a year ago. The
teaching job keeps her busy, and she plans to take her class on a study tour of
Hollywood and Singapore this summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Her other favorite pastime? Watching her old TV shows, especially when her
name appears in the credits.
</P>
<P>
	   "That never gets old," she says.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
	   DAVE'S BACK: He's been off for a month, but tonight David Letterman is back
at his desk on "Late Show." Regis Philbin and Robin Williams are his guests.
Then Dave, who is recovering from heart surgery, will be on hand Wednesday.
Tuesday, Bill Cosby is substitute host, and Thursday, Kathie Lee Gifford perks
things up. Letterman underwent an emergency quintuple bypass operation Jan. 14,
so expect some wry remarks about hospitals. "Late Show with David Letterman"
airs on CBS weeknights at 11:35 p.m. EST.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
