<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Make 'House Calls' Via Web  </HEADLINE>
    By LAURAN NEERGAARD AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congestive heart failure can be really scary -- one day
you're fine, the next you're gasping for air as you're raced to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   If only doctors could catch subtle early warning signs, they potentially
could stave off thousands of panicked hospital visits by adjusting patients'
medications before they worsen.
</P>
<P>
	   But isn't examining a patient every single day impossible?
</P>
<P>
	   Maybe not, thanks to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   In a science fiction-sounding experiment, doctors are implanting tiny
monitors inside the hearts of 120 patients to painlessly record every twinge, 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
	   Sit in front of a doctor's wireless transmitter and the monitor beams the
recordings into a computer for diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
	   But by spring, the study's participants won't have to leave home, instead
spending five minutes a day beaming their Chronicle heart monitor's recordings
to a doctor's secure Web site via a telephone line.
</P>
<P>
	   Consider it an Internet "house call." This doctor-to-home connection is a
hot new area for medical device manufacturers, and it's generating great
interest from doctors frustrated with how to keep chronically ill patients from
worsening at home.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe it's the next generation of care," says Michael Colson of
Medtronic Inc., which is developing the experimental Chronicle system.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the future for chronic disease management -- heart failure,
diabetes, asthma," adds Dr. Richard Miller, director of the Mercy Heart
Institute in Sacramento, Calif., who is using a simpler online monitor, the
Health Buddy.
</P>
<P>
	   Why concentrate first on heart failure? It's so severe that studies should
be able to determine fairly quickly whether monitors help.
</P>
<P>
	   Four million Americans have heart failure, a number expected to double
within 30 years as the population ages and more people survive heart attacks
only to live with a weakened heart that struggles to pump.
</P>
<P>
	   Heart failure costs $40 billion in annual health care, two-thirds due to
repeated hospitalizations when fluid builds up in patients' chests, leaving them
gasping, said Dr. Maria Rosa Costanzo of Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical
Center in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   Worsening heart failure sneaks up on patients, who also may have a hard time
strictly adhering to medication and diet, said Costanzo, whose hospital is one
of seven studying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
	   Plus, patients typically wait five days to call a doctor after a symptom
worsens, Miller laments.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors already know at-home follow-up helps:
</P>
<P>
	   Mercy nurses telephoned hundreds of patients several times a month to quiz
them on symptoms and weight -- even a slight weight gain suggests fluid buildup.
By adjusting medications and alerting doctors to early problems, the telephone
program lowered rehospitalizations by 79 percent. But it's labor-intensive.
</P>
<P>
	   So Miller turned to the Health Buddy, made by California-based Health Hero
Network. Hook the answering machine-size gadget to a telephone line. Nurses'
questions zip through the phone line to the Health Buddy video screen. Patients
click a few buttons to respond to a secure Internet site.
</P>
<P>
	   Miller calls it "a baby step" toward full online monitoring but says
patients "love it. They feel as though they're in touch with a caregiver on a
daily basis."
</P>
<P>
	   The Food and Drug Administration just approved a Health Buddy version that
transmits diabetics' blood-sugar test results straight to doctors.
</P>
<P>
	   Medtronic's Chronicle is still more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
	   Surgeons thread the pacemaker-like device into the heart, to measure
pressure and other subtle disease signs that until now only in-hospital cardiac
catheterizations could provide.
</P>
<P>
	   For now, weekly doctor visits download the recordings, which can alert if a
medication change is needed before there's a crisis, Costanzo said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Medtronic hopes to ship patients at-home transmitters by spring. Point
the antenna at the chest and the recordings beam over a phone line to the
doctor.
</P>
<P>
	   "You'll be in touch with these people anywhere in the country," said implant
recipient Edward A. Krzyston, 51, of Hammond, Ind., who's looking forward to
vacationing with his device -- and says he'll no longer wonder if he's imagining
symptoms. "You don't want to sound like a whiner. With this device, it just
records the information and the doctor decides if it's important or not."
</P>
<P>
	   If studies show the Chronicle keeps patients out of the hospital, Medtronic
hopes to apply for FDA approval in about two years.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical issues for The
Associated Press in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
