<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Discuss Consumer Privacy  </HEADLINE>
   By RAF CASERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union was hopeful Monday it could
force a breakthrough in negotiations with the United States on how to protect
consumer data in trans-Atlantic trade, an issue that has long dogged
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
	   Both sides want to wrap up negotiations before the end of next month, but
the EU's executive Commission said talks between U.S. Undersecretary of Commerce
for International Trade David Aaron and chief EU negotiator John Mogg could
yield results as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Aaron and Mogg started talks at EU headquarters Monday morning and announced
a joint news conference for Tuesday afternoon to wrap up three negotiating
sessions.
</P>
<P>
	   The two sides have struggled since last summer to find a solution to the
dispute over a data protection directive issued by the EU.
</P>
<P>
	   The directive, which went into effect in October, authorizes regulators in
each of the 15 EU nations to halt exports of personal data to countries they
believe do not have adequate arrangements to protect the data.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU countries consider the decentralized approach to data protection in
the United States -- a mixture of law and self regulation -- as not meeting the
standards of its new directive.
</P>
<P>
	   So far EU member states have not threatened to disrupt transfers of
information. Some are still trying to decide how to implement the directive.
</P>
<P>
	   The outcome of the talks will have an impact on industries as varied as
airlines, insurance and banking and could affect billions of dollars in trade.
</P>
<P>
	   It raises such questions as whether the distribution and use of airline data
on a passenger's meal preference need the consent of the individual. In the
insurance sector, the free availability of personal health data might raise
ethical questions on the availability of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. companies want an agreement that will ensure that as much personal data
as possible about European consumers can be transferred across the Atlantic.
European human rights campaigners want to prevent this as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
	   The two sides are trying to come up with a so-called safe-harbor agreement
that would allow U.S. industry to conduct business with Europe if they meet
certain private data commitments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
