<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CGU, Norwich Union Plan Merger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- Insurance group CGU PLC plans to acquire Norwich Union PLC
for $12 billion in stock in a deal that would form the largest insurance
business in Britain and fifth-largest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   The consolidation would come at the cost of 5,000 jobs, or 7 percent of the
companies' combined work force.
</P>
<P>
	   The new company, to be called CGNU, will be based in London and will be the
largest provider of general insurance and the second-largest provider of life
insurance in Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal also would give the combined company strong positions in several
European and international markets, said CGU chief executive Bob Scott, who is
to continue in the same role at the new group.
</P>
<P>
	   Shareholders in both companies and British financial authorities still must
approve the transaction.
</P>
<P>
	   The partners estimate that they can save $400 million each year by
consolidating various aspects of the two companies. Half the savings would
result from job cuts, with the remainder expected to come from integrating
computer networks, selling property and other sources, Norwich Union spokesman
James Duffell said.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the deal, Norwich Union shareholders would receive 0.48 shares in the
new group for each Norwich Union share. CGU shareholders would receive one share
in the new group for each CGU share.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, CGU shareholders would control 58.5 percent of the combined
group, while Norwich Union shareholders would control 41.5 percent. CGU also
would appoint nine of the group's 17 directors.
</P>
<P>
	   NU chief executive Richard Harvey, who will become deputy chief executive in
the combined group, said the deal would create significant value for both sets
of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
	   CGU shares surged on the announcement, but later fell to 785 pence ($12.45)
each, down 11 pence on the London Stock Exchange. Norwich Union shares initially
rose before finishing down 9 percent, or 39 pence, to 396.25 pence ($6.29) each.
</P>
<P>
	   Duffell acknowledged that an outside company could disrupt the marriage if
it were to make an offer for either or both companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Although both Norwich Union and CGU have long planned their move, neither
set of shareholders would receive a premium as the deal is structured.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal is the latest in a wave of consolidation that has swept Britain's
insurance and financial services sectors. Royal Bank of Scotland won a $33.6
billion takeover bid for National Westminster earlier this month, while Lloyds
TSB acquired the insurance group Scottish Widows last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1423 </TRAILER>
