<HEADLINE> EU, Latin Nations Seek Deeper Ties  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY HATTON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VILAMOURA, Portugal (AP) -- Leaders of the European Union and Latin American
nations are aiming to deepen economic and political ties in three days of talks
beginning Tuesday in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU is eager to expand trade with Latin America, fearing it could lose
ground to the United States, which is seeking to create a Pan-American
free-trade area by 2005.
</P>
<P>
	   The talks among government ministers from the EU and Latin America are to
build on last summer's summit meeting, which was a first step toward a
free-trade deal with South America's strongest economies.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU aims to sign a free-trade deal with Mexico next month, although the
accord still must be ratified by the European Parliament, the legislatures of
Belgium, Italy, Denmark and Luxembourg, and the Mexican Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU also is to discuss prospects for a free-trade deal with the Mercosur
nations of Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay, Uruguay and Chile -- South America's
strongest economies -- during the meetings in southern Portugal.
</P>
<P>
	   Portugal currently holds the EU's rotating presidency. The EU already is the
main trading partner of the Mercosur nations, ahead of the United States and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   EU companies are eager to expand their presence in Latin America's
industrial and service sectors. Some companies already have invested heavily in
privatization efforts in Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU has put together an 11-point program that seeks to promote human
rights and good governance in Latin countries.
</P>
<P>
	   An EU meeting with a half dozen Central American nations was to begin the
talks. The Europeans plan to seek assurances that countries struck in October
1998 by Hurricane Mitch, which killed nearly 10,000 people, will use EU aid
totaling about $250 million. Some $80 million in reconstruction aid still must
be allocated.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, EU officials are to meet with Mexican officials to discuss a
planned visit to Lisbon next month by President Ernesto Zedillo. The Mexican
president is to sign a free-trade accord on the sidelines of an EU summit
meeting in the Portuguese capital.
</P>
<P>
	   The accord foresees free trade in industrial goods by 2007 and in farm
products by 2010.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU wants to conclude its pact with Mexico so its member states can
compete effectively with the United States and Canada, which will have duty-free
access to Mexican markets by 2003 under the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   The free-trade talks with the four Mercosur countries face no formal
deadline since their fate depends on the evolution of trade talks through the
World Trade Organization, which are now deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, the EU is to meet with the Andean Pact nations of Bolivia,
Peru, Ecuador and Colombia. These countries want the EU to treat them on an
equal basis as the Mercosur nations, something the Europeans refuse to do
because of those countries' weak economic integration with their neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
