<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Kohl To Be Spared Search  </HEADLINE>
   By BURT HERMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl will be spared the
embarrassment -- at least for now -- of having his homes and offices searched
for evidence of breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
	   Roland Wangen, a spokesman for Bonn prosecutors, said Monday that a weekend
report in Der Spiegel magazine about the planned search eliminates the element
of surprise.
</P>
<P>
	   Such searches are successful only ``when the person concerned has no
knowledge ahead of time,'' Wangen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors would have needed permission from the parliament to do the
search because Kohl retains his seat there and therefore has immunity.
</P>
<P>
	   Files relating to the sale of the former East German Leuna oil refinery to
France's Elf Aquitaine already have been reported missing from the chancellery
office. There are allegations that Aquitaine paid Kohl's party kickbacks in
order to seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Wangen raised the possibility of criminal action against those responsible
for leaking news of the search, but said it was still more important to continue
the investigation against Kohl.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors had also wanted to search the offices and homes of Kohl's office
manager and driver.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl's admission that he accepted $1 million touched off the scandal over
years of illegal financial practices by the Christian Democrats, including
secret accounts to evade campaign finance laws and defrauding the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl lawyer Stephan Holthoff-Pfoertner called a potential search a
``senseless action,'' telling the Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung that it would
only serve to ``degrade Kohl's character.''
</P>
<P>
	   Also granted a reprieve in the scandal Monday was the embattled governor of
Hesse state, whose own network of secret accounts has shown the Christian
Democrat party branch there to be just as corrupt as the national party.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors in Wiesbaden said they would not pursue a criminal investigation
against Roland Koch, who over the weekend was re-elected as head of the state
party branch in an overwhelming show of confidence.
</P>
<P>
	   Werner Roth, head prosecutor in Wiesbaden, said there was not enough
evidence to begin an investigation against Koch, who took office just a year
ago. Other party leaders have also defended Koch against calls for him to
resign, saying he had no role in setting up the secret accounts that stretch
back to 1971 -- the year Kohl took over as chairman of the federal party.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch has belatedly admitted he knew the state party had filed a false
financial report for 1998, characterizing $750,000 as a loan when it actually
stemmed from one of the party's slush fund.
</P>
<P>
	   That false report led the federal party to also carry the misstated amount
over to its 1998 financial report, which is used by the federal government to
determine the matching campaign funds parties receive. The federal party earlier
this month was ordered to pay back $20.6 million it had received in matching
federal funds following the illegal 1998 report.
</P>
<P>
	   Responding to the prosecutors' decision, Koch said he hoped he would now be
freed from nearly daily accusations of being a swindler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1426 </TRAILER>
