<DOCNO> APW20000221.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More classes, convenient study methods attracting different types  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HOBOKEN, N.J. (AP) - Anthony Racioppi is 47, and he's made a commitment.
<P>
	   "This is something I've been wanting to do for a long time," said Racioppi,
a firefighter for the North Hudson Regional Fire Department in North Bergen.
</P>
<P>
	   He isn't referring to marriage. He's decided to become certified open water
scuba diver and has been taking classes at the Hoboken Dive Center.
</P>
<P>
	   Scuba organizations and dive shops offering a variety of class schedules
have enabled the $1.5 billion-a-year industry to attract people who otherwise
wouldn't have the chance to experience a world most people never get to see.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's the peacefulness of it," said Racioppi, who has completed several pool
sessions required for certification. "I remember watching the 'Diver Dan'
cartoon when I was about 6, and then it was 'Sea Hunt' when I was older. I could
never get certified because I had no time, but that flexibility of going to
class on Tuesday nights was good for me."
</P>
<P>
	   Robert Powley, 34, is an attorney who is also a dive instructor. He's been
teaching since 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   "I get everybody from actors to investment bankers," he said. "I think most
people get into it because they tend to be a little bit more adventurous. It's a
super-safe sport, but people tend to think it's much more dangerous than it is."
</P>
<P>
	   Today, there are about 8.5 million certified scuba divers, according to
PADI. The average diver is 36 years old. Half are college educated and earn over
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the majority - over 70 percent - of recreational divers are men,
the number of women involved in the sport is on the rise. Their numbers
increased by 112 percent from 1989 to 1999, according to the Professional
Association of Diving Instructors (PADI), the world's largest scuba
organization, which certifies 70 percent of divers in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
	   Colleen Bush, 38, of Fairview started diving around 1987 after being
certified a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   "I dragged my husband skiing, so he dragged me to go diving," said Bush, who
now works at the Hoboken Dive Center.
</P>
<P>
	   She recalled what it was like aboard boats on her first dives.
</P>
<P>
	   "Most of the guys are really great, but sometimes some of them will look at
you like, 'What are you doing here?' There's still some of that," Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   The industry is also beginning to target another group - children - and is
now marketing equipment made especially for them.
</P>
<P>
	   "So many of us in the business started as kids, and I saw a study somewhere
that said the best way to get a person to stick with a sport is to start them
young. We in the industry have just begun to recognize that," said David
Stancil, vice president for Aqua Lung America Inc., headquartered in Vista,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   As with skiing, diving involves a substantial initial outlay for equipment.
A new diver should plan on spending about $1,200, which includes a BCD (buoyancy
control device), air-flow regulators, tanks, weight belt, fins, mask and
snorkel.
</P>
<P>
	   Certification courses can run between $100 and $300, depending on location
and class size. PADI or NAUI (National Association of Underwater Instructors)
require written work and four check-out dives accompanied by an instructor.
</P>
<P>
	   Like a passport, the certification cards are recognized at shops and resorts
around the world, allowing individuals access to equipment and the water.
</P>
<P>
	   Diving can be physically taxing, and there are risks. Instructors typically
recommend getting a physical prior to taking a class, but industry officials say
the sport is less dangerous than people generally think.
</P>
<P>
	   "Per 100,000 participants, there are as many accidents as you would have in
badminton - literally," said Jeff Nadler, vice president of industry relations
for PADI. "There are three times more accidents in swimming as a recreational
activity," said Nadler, referring to statistics from the National Safety
Council.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1999, 85 people were killed in diving-relating accidents in North
American waters, including the Caribbean and Canada, according to Divers Alert
Network (DAN), an organization that provides insurance for scuba divers.
</P>
<P>
	   "But 25 to 30 percent of those cases are attributable to cardiac events, so
it may not be diving that caused those deaths, but rather poor physical
fitness," said Dan Nord, a paramedic at the Durham, N.C.-based organization who
works with injured divers.
</P>
<P>
	   "As divers, we like people to think that it's dangerous because it makes us
look cooler," said Pat Iapicca, owner of the Hoboken Dive Center. "In reality,
90 percent of the entire sport is getting over the anxiety, and once you get
over it, it's all downhill."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
