<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill would permit New Jersey judges to earn income from side jobs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - "I think my term paper deserved a better grade that
a B-minus, your honor."
<P>
	   Picture a judge in the classroom moonlighting as a teacher, or working on
the side as a ski instructor, TV show host or tour guide. Or earning extra
income as a free-lance legal writer or lecturer.
</P>
<P>
	   Judges moonlight at all of these jobs and more in most other states, but New
Jersey law prohibits Superior Court judges from collecting salary for anything
on the side.
</P>
<P>
	   Assemblyman Michael Carroll, R-Morris, has introduced a bill, ACR-93, to
that would permit them to earn outside income as long as the work does not
interfere with court business or conflict with any cases they're hearing.
</P>
<P>
	   The relatively low pay for New Jersey judges, who often earn less than the
lawyers appearing before them, has been long been a source of discontent in
legal circles.
</P>
<P>
	   But Chief Justice Deborah Poritz, for one, is against the idea of allowing
them to accept outside income and recently testified before an Assembly
committee that judicial work requires full-time attention.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey is one of only three states that bar moonlighting, which is also
allowable for federal judges. To enact the change here, however, lawmakers must
propose a constitutional amendment that would require voter approval in a
November referendum.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll said it would be an asset for the state's legal system to expose law
students to experienced judges either as adjunct teachers or on the lecture
circuit.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need some incentive to get those men and women in the acme of their
career into the classroom," he told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Monday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll sponsored a bill passed in January to boost Superior Court judges'
salaries from $115,000 to $141,000 over the next three years. The same bill will
increase lawmakers' salaries in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting that law school graduates can secure positions paying $120,000 a
year, Carroll said more liberal financial rules are needed if the state is to
continue enticing qualified lawyers out of private firms and to the bench.
Carroll, who is a lawyer, concedes there is no shortage of people interested in
becoming judges, though he said he worries that the most qualified lawyers shy
away from the job.
</P>
<P>
	   But in her testimony before the Legislature in support of pay raises for
judges, Poritz dismissed the idea of judicial income from off the bench.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our judges live by the strictest code of ethics in the nation and are
barred from outside employment by the New Jersey Constitution, and properly so,
because being a judge in New Jersey is a full-time job and more," Poritz said.
</P>
<P>
	   Retired Supreme Court Justice Stewart Pollock, who frequently gave lectures
without compensation and who put four children though college on a justice's
salary, told the newspaper the current system works well and should not be
tinkered with.
</P>
<P>
	   Pollock said New Jersey's judiciary enjoys a good reputation nationwide in
part because judges are utterly free from outside influences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 1506 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
