<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Law Prompts Nigerian Clash  </HEADLINE>
   By GILBERT DA COSTA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Rioting Muslim and Christian youths seized parts of
the northern city of Kaduna on Monday in clashes over a proposal to bring
Islamic law to the state. More than 20 people were killed, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
	   The violence began when hundreds of Christian demonstrators marched through
the streets chanting ``No to sharia! No to sharia!''
</P>
<P>
	   Counter-chants by Muslims who support sharia, or Islamic law, quickly
degenerated into fighting between the two groups, said the witnesses, who spoke
by telephone on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   By the afternoon, the two sides had gained control of different
neighborhoods and divided the city into warring zones.
</P>
<P>
	   Police largely stayed away from the fighting but cruised the city with
sirens blaring.
</P>
<P>
	   A witness said he saw at least 20 bodies in one Kaduna neighborhood. Other
corpses were spotted elsewhere. Bonfires raged throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
	   The St. Joseph Roman Catholic cathedral and the nearby central mosque were
both set ablaze.
</P>
<P>
	   State Gov. Ahmad Maikarfi imposed a 6:00 p.m. to 6:00 a.m. curfew throughout
the city. Military and police were put on high alert. Most civilians remained at
home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are working hard to bring the situation under control,'' state police
commissioner Hamisu Isah said. The city of Kaduna, the state capital, is about
120 miles north of Nigeria's capital, Abuja.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharia went into effect without incident last month in nearby Zamfara state,
which is overwhelmingly Muslim. Muslim law prohibits such things as drinking
alcohol and also calls for separate schools and public transportation for males
and females. Islamic courts were established to try and mete out punishment to
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
	   A number of other states in Nigeria's largely Muslim north -- including
Kaduna -- are considering following suit. About 40 percent of Kaduna state is
Christian.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters say changes brought by sharia will not affect Christians, and
that Christians will be allowed to seek redress in secular courts. But the issue
has become increasingly divisive in Nigeria, a nation of 120 million people with
a long history of bloody ethnic and religious violence.
</P>
<P>
	   Christian leaders across the country have denounced the arrival of Islamic
law, and newspapers based in the largely Christian south fill pages with ominous
headlines warning that non-Muslims will face bitter discrimination.
</P>
<P>
	   Political leaders in Nigeria, where 15 years of military rule gave way to
democratic elections last year, have remained largely quiet on the topic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1528 </TRAILER>
