<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group once allied with Pataki now running anti-Pataki ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A conservative anti-tax group that was once strongly
allied with Gov. George Pataki has started to run commercials across much of the
state lambasting his tax policies and economic treatment of upstate New York.
<P>
	   The television and radio ads look and sound like something that would come
from Democrats seeking to drive the Republican governor from office. They are
really from Change-New York.
</P>
<P>
	   The group has come to the conclusion that the Pataki of the 1994 campaign
and his first two years in office is not the Pataki who now resides in the
Executive Mansion, spokesman Brian Backstrom said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think that there is a mentality, 'Tax cuts? We've done those. Hold the
line on spending? We've done that,"' Backstrom said. "We thought we were in this
for a marriage. We only got the honeymoon."
</P>
<P>
	   The group is particularly angered about a $400 million increase on state
cigarette taxes approved by Pataki and the state Legislature in December as well
as a proposed 2000-01 state budget from the governor that Change-New York
believes would increase spending by twice the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not the behavior of fiscal conservatives," Backstrom contended.
"One of the reasons we felt a media campaign was warranted was this latest round
of tax hikes and excessive spending was not a blip on the radar screen, but the
next giant step of an intentional move leftward."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said the group knows it is "deliberately
distorting the facts" with an ad which says upstate New York, if taken as a
separate state, has had job growth ranked 49th nationally since Pataki has
become governor.
</P>
<P>
	   "Upstate is growing jobs faster than many places, such as Illinois, Ohio,
North Carolina and Pennsylvania," McKeon said. "In fact, upstate has more jobs
now than ever before. It's a far cry from the final years of the Cuomo
administration. New Yorkers are not going to be fooled by these misleading ads."
</P>
<P>
	   The group has two anti-Pataki TV ads, one showing scenes of Niagara Falls
and other flowing waters and criticizing Pataki for proposing a fee on water
hookups. The money was to have gone to fund water-quality programs in the state,
though Pataki's office indicated the governor was backing off the proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   The other TV ad says: "While Wall Street is booming, upstate New York is
being left behind." If upstate is treated as a separate state, the commercial
says it would be 49th in the country in job creation since Pataki became
governor in 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor Pataki," the ad implores, "stop hiking our taxes. Get back to
cutting them."
</P>
<P>
	   Backstrom said the ads are running in major upstate New York television
markets. He declined to say how much the group was paying for the commercials,
how long they will run or if others are in the works. He said the group will
stop airing the "water tax" commercial in light of Pataki's decision to back off
that proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno called the ads "very, very
one-sided" and "unfair." He complained they make no reference to the tax cuts
enacted under Pataki, estimated as having a cumulative savings for taxpayers of
a highest-in-the-nation $29 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno said he was also taken aback by the source of the criticism.
</P>
<P>
	   "They were his biggest supporter in the first election (in 1994) so that's
why this is so surprising," he said on WROW-AM radio in Albany. "These ads are
almost vindictive."
</P>
<P>
	   Among the members of Change-New York's board are two financiers who have
contributed generously to his campaigns in the past, Richard Gilder and Bruce
Kovner.
</P>
<P>
	   Backstrom said top Change-New York officials were angered when Pataki failed
to show up for a scheduled meeting with them to discuss his taxing and other
policies.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki insists his budget increases general fund spending by just over 2
percent or about the rate of inflation, but the overall increase when all funds
are factored in would be more than 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 1549 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore and Bradley at the Apollo - debate night in Harlem  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Warming up for their debut at the Apollo, Al Gore walked
the streets of Harlem enjoying the advantages of being Bill Clinton's vice
president while Bill Bradley questioned Gore's willingness to help people who
don't have health insurance.
<P>
	   The Democratic presidential rivals were meeting late Monday at the Apollo
Theatre, a Harlem landmark, in a 90-minute debate on urban and racial issues.
State party officials estimate that between 35 percent and 40 percent of voters
in New York's Democratic primary on March 7 will be black and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls give Gore a prohibitive lead among minority voters, much of it
inherited from his shared tenure with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   Davita Cook, a forensic science student, called after Gore as he and Rep.
Charlie Rangel, D-N.Y., picked their way down Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard,
past the Harlem Farmers Market and Uptown Jean Co., where two-piece sets of
thermal underwear advertised for $5.99.
</P>
<P>
	   "Do you promise to pick up where Clinton left off? Do you promise to stay
true?" the woman called out to Gore, who did not respond.
</P>
<P>
	   Cook told a reporter she was voting for Gore "only because he is following
in Clinton's footsteps; it's Clinton we adore."
</P>
<P>
	   Jose Pena, an immigrant from Santo Domingo showed off the voter registration
card that identified him as a Democrat. "I have three babies. I need a job," the
man told Gore in halting English. Gore referred him to a caseworker in Rangel's
local office.
</P>
<P>
	   Across the street, the Apollo marquee advertised "Amateur Night" and made no
mention of the face-off between Gore and Bradley - their first since Gore
solidified his front-runner status with wins in Iowa and New Hampshire. Bradley
has since slipped far behind in some polls and is struggling to build a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides promised a more combative candidate for the two-week sprint to "Super
Tuesday" when more than a dozen states will vote. Bradley scheduled a speech on
Tuesday on Long Island that was being billed as the kickoff of an effort to
expose inconsistencies and dishonesty in Gore's record.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore campaign strategist Bill Knapp dismissed the pumped-up strategy by
saying, "He's going to throw battery acid around." Knapp said Gore's own sharp
critique of Bradley and his agenda was different because Gore is "just defending
his record and saying what he wants to do as president."
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Bradley talked tough before 100 or so parents and other local
residents as he campaigned at Brooklyn's P.S. 24 with City Councilman Angel
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
	   Calling health care "an American birthright," Bradley, who has proposed a
plan for universal access to health insurance, warned that voters should be
skeptical of Gore's criticism of that plan. "I am disappointed that Al Gore has
attacked and distorted it. It casts doubt on his commitment to a basic plank in
the Democratic platform."
</P>
<P>
	   Universal health care has been part of the Democratic Party's platform for
nearly 40 years, Bradley said. "Now is the opportunity to make good on that
promise."
</P>
<P>
	   Eric Banks, an art teacher at a Brooklyn high school, called Bradley a
little too liberal for his taste. But Banks also said he was voting for Bradley
because, "He's more open-minded than Gore."
</P>
<P>
	   Among the Clinton administration achievements for which Gore sought a share
of credit on Monday were the federal "empowerment zone" investments that have
attracted businesses to formerly rundown urban centers like the main street in
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
	   As Gore briefly ducked into an Old Navy store to ask shoppers for their
votes, aides told reporters that Harlem was one of the empowerment zones that
Gore worked on with Rangel.
</P>
<P>
	   Omitted was a crucial piece of legislative history: that it was Bradley who,
as a senator from New Jersey in 1993, wrote the blueprint for the empowerment
zones and - with Rangel, then-Rep. Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois and New York
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan - was instrumental in pushing the legislation
through Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
