<HEADLINE> Business news in brief from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HOUSTON (AP) - Reliant Energy announced Monday it will pay $2.1 billion
to buy 21 power plants from a privately held electricity producer whose
generators dot the Middle Atlantic region.
<P>
	   Sixteen of the plants Reliant is acquiring from Sithe Energies are in
Pennsylvania, with four in New Jersey and one in Maryland. The deal gives
Houston-based Reliant a major foothold in one of five regions the company is
targeting as it expands its unregulated power generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
	   The four New Jersey plants that have been acquired are located in Forked
River, Kenilworth, Sayreville, Glen Gardner.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale is expected to be finalized by midyear.
</P>
<P>
	   New York-based Sithe is one of the largest independent power producers in
the United States. It is owned 60 percent by the French water and utilities
giant Vivendi, 29 percent by the Japanese trading firm Marubeni and 11 percent
by its two cofounders. ----
</P>
<P>
	   CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) - Subaru of America Inc. and L.L. Bean announced
Monday that they have entered into a multiyear marketing partnership.
</P>
<P>
	   The partnership establishes Subaru as the official vehicle of L.L. Bean and
L.L. Bean as the official outfitter to Subaru.
</P>
<P>
	   Central to the agreement are a Subaru Outback Limited Special L.L. Bean
Edition available later this year in the U.S. and Canada, an L.L. Bean gear and
apparel program for Subaru and its dealers and L.L. Bean presence at selected
Subaru-sponsored outdoor events.
</P>
<P>
	   L.L. Bean Inc., headquartered in Freeport, Maine, is a retailer of
outdoor-oriented gear and apparel. Subaru of America Inc., a wholly owned
subsidiary of Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. of Japan, markets and distributes
Subaru vehicles, parts and accessories through a network of nearly 600
franchised dealers in the U.S. ----
</P>
</TEXT>
