<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki to expand eligibility limits for fuel aid program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - After being given the green light by the Clinton
administration, Gov. George Pataki said Monday he will ask that more
lower-income New Yorkers become eligible for a federal home heating oil
assistance program.
<P>
	   Pataki said he will change the income standards for the Home Energy
Assistance Program (HEAP). Currently, families within 150 percent of the poverty
level qualify for the program in New York, but Pataki said he'd change the
eligibility standard by making it 60 percent of the state's median income.
</P>
<P>
	   Two people making $16,596 a year or less currently qualify for the HEAP
program. That income total would increase to $22,812 using the 60 percent of
median income standard.
</P>
<P>
	   For a family of four, the income threshold would increase from $25,056 to
$33,547.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, U.S. Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala wrote
to 18 governors, including Pataki, reminding them that they have the power to
expand the eligibility standards under HEAP.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton last week made another $125 million available under HEAP
and asked Congress to appropriate a new $600 million.
</P>
<P>
	   So far this year, New York has received $73 million in HEAP benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki on Monday continued to call on Clinton to release some of the
nation's petroleum reserves to ease the pricing crisis, a move the president has
resisted so far.
</P>
<P>
	   The price spike was created by the decision of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to reduce output by 4.3 million barrels a day and
exacerbated by frigid weather in January in the Northeast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
