<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reformers Win Parliament Seats  </HEADLINE>
   By VIJAY JOSHI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Reformists led in voting for most of Tehran's
parliament seats Monday and looked set to sweep there -- a victory that would
guarantee them a parliamentary majority with dozens of other seats still left to
be decided nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   The results sent a clear message to the hard-line clergy that Iranians are
fed up with their 21-year restrictive rule that dictates day-to-day lives. They
were also an endorsement of President Mohamed Khatami, who has advocated
dismantling many social and political restrictions since he came to power in
1997.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was a vote to legalize and institutionalize Khatami's reforms. Our
priority now is to make a serious effort to defend people's rights,'' said
reformist candidate Meysam Saeedi.
</P>
<P>
	   Parliament has been dominated by hard-liners since 1979, when the Islamic
revolution installed the Shiite clergy's rule. Hard-liners have obstructed
Khatami at every step during his term. They have used special courts to jail his
allies, and pro-conservative vigilantes have attacked reformist politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   Vote counts from Friday's election were still trickling in Monday, and final
results were not expected to be announced until later in the week. But so far,
the reformists have won 137 of 191 seats in the 290-member parliament, or
Majlis. The conservatives have won 44 and independents 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Sixty-nine seats will not be decided until run-off elections in April. But
even now, a simple majority of 146 is within the reformists' reach. Their
candidates were leading the vote count in 26 of Tehran's 30 races.
</P>
<P>
	   The loss of Tehran will be particularly humiliating to the hard-liners, who
had fielded some of their top candidates there against equally high-profile
reformers, including Khatami's younger brother, Mohammadreza Khatami.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States, Russia and Turkey welcomed the results. In the past,
encouraged by Khatami's attitude, many reformers had suggested reopening talks
with the United States, which used to be reviled by Iran as the ``Great Satan.''
</P>
<P>
	   The hard-liners see the ruling clerics as the unquestionable interpreters of
God's word. Khatami, by contrast, believes in the rule of law and people's right
to make their own choices about their lives, such as the music they listen to or
the clothes they wear.
</P>
<P>
	   The reformist sweep has been such that leaders even loosely associated with
the hard-liners -- former President Hashemi Rafsanjani, for example -- have been
defeated. Although a moderate, voters saw Rafsanjani as untrustworthy after he
failed to stand up for reformists jailed by hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
	   It remains to be seen whether the hard-liners will continue to thwart the
reformists when the new legislature convenes in June. Despite their likely loss
of parliament, the hard-liners still control the Guardian Council, a supervisory
body that approves all bills parliament passes. They also oversee the judiciary,
the armed forces and radio and television stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1633 </TRAILER>
