<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philbin Apparently Feeling Deprived  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID BAUDER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Giving away all that money on "Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire" apparently has host Regis Philbin feeling a little deprived.
</P>
<P>
	   He picked a high-profile venue -- David Letterman's first "Late Show" since
heart surgery -- to reveal he isn't happy that ABC hasn't rewarded him for his
role on television's most popular prime-time show.
</P>
<P>
	   "How's your little quiz show doing?" Letterman asked Philbin, one of his
guests on the show taped Friday that was to air Monday. "Are you making a lot of
dough?"
</P>
<P>
	   "No, I'm not," Philbin replied.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those pantywaists at ABC are not paying you what you're worth?" Letterman
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think so," Philbin said, then quickly tried to change the subject
back to Letterman's bypass operation.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no immediate reply to a phone message and a page left for ABC
representatives on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Philbin signed on as "Millionaire" host last year, when it was supposed to
be a limited summer replacement series on ABC. He even privately campaigned for
the job after being intrigued by the British version of the game show.
</P>
<P>
	   It quickly became a television phenomenon that now runs three times a week
in prime time, sometimes more. Philbin's question to contestants, "is that your
final answer," is a national catchphrase.
</P>
<P>
	   "Millionaire" is singlehandedly responsible for ABC's leap past CBS and NBC
into first place in the prime-time ratings this season.
</P>
<P>
	   Philbin said, during an interview in October before "Millionaire" became a
regular series, that he had signed a five-year contract to be host. At the time,
he said he had not sought to renegotiate with ABC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
