<HEADLINE> Ukraine To Let Currency Float  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- The Ukrainian government and central bank announced
Monday that the national currency, the hryvna, is being allowed to float after
years of trying to keep its value within a trading band.
</P>
<P>
	   The move aims "to assist Ukraine's integration into the world market," the
Cabinet and the bank said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Previously, Ukraine tried to keep the official rate within a "trading
corridor;" the most recent trading band was 3.4 to 4.6 hryvna to the dollar. But
street trading, seen as a more reliable indicator of the currency's real value
than the official rate, put the hryvna at 5.57 to the dollar on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The move "will keep Ukrainian goods competitive and enterprises profitable,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   "At the same time, the Cabinet and the National Bank will closely follow the
country's economic development and the situation on the currency market in order
to protect the monetary system, ensure the stability of the hryvna and pursue a
currency policy that will promote Ukraine's economic growth," the statement
said, according to the news agency Interfax.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Monday, a top government official said an audit of the National Bank
and an inspection of Ukraine's use of International Monetary Fund credits will
be conducted.
</P>
<P>
	   An IMF mission held a final meeting with Prime Minister Viktor Yushchenko
before their scheduled departure Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Agreements were reached "on many points," mission leader Mohammad
Shadman-Valavi said after the meeting, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent stories in the Financial Times have claimed the central bank misused
IMF loans in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The paper based its story on the evidence of former Premier Pavlo Lazarenko,
who was charged with money laundering and is currently in custody in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has denied the allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
