<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Boosts Fee To Help BBC  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- The government decided Monday to raise the annual fee
citizens pay to watch television to help the state-supported British
Broadcasting Corp. fund its digital TV expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
	   The fee, currently $160, will increase by 1.5 percent above the rate of
inflation for seven years beginning this April, Culture Secretary Chris Smith
told the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
	   That translates to a $4.80 increase this year -- far less than the BBC
wanted.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith said the boosted fee would give the BBC about $320 million extra
through 2006, but added that the corporation must in turn raise $1.6 billion
itself through internal savings and external funding.
</P>
<P>
	   "As well as providing a greater variety of programs, the BBC must become
even more cost-effective and quality-conscious," Smith said. "Extra funding must
also be accompanied by improved accountability."
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, an independent panel had proposed a separate $38.40 fee be
imposed on viewers already receiving digital channels to help meet the extra
$1.12 billion the BBC had said it needed for its plans.
</P>
<P>
	   The corporation wants to establish new digital channels and further develop
its existing digital outlets and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, the BBC's bosses gave the government's announcement a cautious
welcome, saying the certainty of extra funding for the next seven years was
comforting but that some plans would have to be scaled down.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's less than we asked for, but it's above the rate of inflation and the
BBC will do its best to make the best use of it in broadcasting terms," chairman
Sir Christopher Bland said.
</P>
<P>
	   Refusing to rule out staff cutbacks, Bland said: "In terms of job losses,
it's far too soon to say whether there will be any."
</P>
<P>
	   He said details of how the corporation proposed to make efficiency savings
would be made public "in a couple of months."
</P>
<P>
	   Several of the BBC's commercial rivals said they were pleased the government
had not imposed a separate digital fee. But they noted that the corporation was
still getting a decided advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a huge payday for the BBC," said Tony Ball, chief executive of
British Sky Broadcasting. "Despite the culture secretary's recognition that the
BBC needs to raise its game and be more cost-effective, the corporation is being
given millions more in public money."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1648 </TRAILER>
