<HEADLINE> NFC, Ocean Group To Merge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- Ocean Group PLC and NFC PLC on Monday announced a merger that
will create a heavyweight in the transportation and logistics business.
</P>
<P>
	   The two companies said the deal will be "a merger of equals," which will
create a new company, Exel PLC, with revenue of $5.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Exel will serve some two-thirds of the world's 250 largest companies,
excluding financial institutions, and have global coverage, they said.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said the two businesses are complementary and the deal gives the
new entity critical mass in the fast-growing market for outsourced logistics.
</P>
<P>
	   "Each company acquires its perfect partner for no premium and no cash," said
Gerry Murphy, chief executive of NFC at a press conference in London.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy chose to step aside and will have no responsibility in Exel, while
John Allan, chief executive of Ocean Group, will be chief executive.
</P>
<P>
	   "This enables us to be a world leader in supply chain management with strong
positions in the U.S. and Europe and a growing business in Asia," Allan said.
</P>
<P>
	   Exel will rank number two in the field of integrated logistics in terms of
sales, behind Germany's Deutsche Post and before U.S. CNF Transportation Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Ocean Group's focus is on technology, health care and fashion, while NFC's
strength is in the automotive, electronics, chemicals, consumer and retail
sectors.
</P>
<P>
	   Ocean Group's Allan said the two companies were looking to complete the
merger in three months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
