<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communists Lead in Kyrgyzstan Race  </HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT FRANCE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BISHKEK, Kyrgyzstan (AP) -- Communists held a solid advantage over
pro-government parties in vote counting Monday from Kyrgyzstan's parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
	   Reports of fraud and voting irregularities also surfaced following Sunday
balloting, further casting doubt on the legitimacy of elections already
tarnished by the exclusion of most of the country's opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
	   Kyrgyzstan, an impoverished mountainous country of 4 million people, had
been considered the most democratic nation to emerge from the former Soviet
Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
	   But that reputation has been hurt by concerns about the fairness of the vote
along with recent efforts by President Askar Akayev -- the country's leader
since the 1991 breakup of the Soviet Union -- to crack down on dissent.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the vote was going against the president's allies, the government
insisted the election had gone smoothly. ``The elections were free and fair,''
said Sulaiman Imanbaev, chairman of the Central Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   Only 11 out of 27 political parties registered in Kyrgyzstan were allowed to
compete, and most of the main opposition parties were barred from fielding their
strongest candidates because of minor technicalities.
</P>
<P>
	   With about 57 percent of the vote counted, the Communists had 26.4 percent.
The pro-government Union of Democratic Forces had 16.3 percent, and the
Democratic Party of Women had 13 percent, elections officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   By excluding the opposition, Kyrgyzstan reneged on commitments as a member
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, said the vice
president of the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly, Igor Otash.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The overall result of those decisions was a considerable restriction of
political alternatives for the electorate,'' Otash told the Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Tensions ran high in areas where opposition candidates were barred from the
race, but police were out in large numbers to keep control, and no violence was
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   At the Jalal-Abad University in southern Kyrgyzstan, teachers stood outside
the polling station, handing out poll invitations to students who had already
voted once. The students were then permitted to vote a second time without
showing their passports.
</P>
<P>
	   Claudia Svyatkina, head of the university's election commission, said:
``There's been pressure from the government everywhere, including here.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was discipline during Soviet times,'' she said. ``What we have now
is not democracy but anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Outside a polling station in Bishkek, voter Sergei Gavrilin said, ``I
received invitations to vote at two precincts.''
</P>
<P>
	   Observers in Osh and Jalal-Abad reported Monday they were not allowed to
watch ballot-counting as required by law. In Bishkek, election commissioners
changed voting results while a television news crew filmed them.
</P>
<P>
	   A total of 545 candidates competed for 105 seats in the two houses of
parliament. Many ran as independents, preferring to keep their party
affiliations unofficial to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   A second round of voting will be held March 5 in districts in which no
candidate won at least 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1731 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
