<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Fashion Goes Beyond Runway  </HEADLINE>
    By DANIELA PETROFF AP Fashion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Fashion and boats, fashion and song festivals, fashion
and movies -- there's almost as much happening off the runway as on during this
week of preview showings for fall-winter 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Far away from the hubbub of the "moda Milanese" presentations that began
over the weekend, a sailboat christened Luna Rossa -- but better known as Prada
-- is vying for America's Cup in the bay of Auckland in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
	   The boat is owned by Patrizio Bertelli, husband of designer Miuccia Prada
and manager of the multimillion-dollar fashion empire. Miuccia unveiled her new
collection Monday evening hours before the Prada team was scheduled to set sail
for the cup's second regatta. The first was won by New Zealand's Black Magic
defender of the cup.
</P>
<P>
	   The Prada boat has become a matter of national pride, with millions of
Italians staying up all night to watch the races live. Between one tack and
another they can also admire the team's outfits, designed by Miuccia. Prada
sailing caps are already selling like hot cakes at more than $100 a shot.
</P>
<P>
	   Back in Italy another national pastime, the San Remo song festival, will
also have Italians glued to their TV screens throughout the week. Designers
Giorgio Armani and Valentino have been called in to dress one of the co-hosts,
Spanish model Ines Sastri, in outfits from their latest collections.
</P>
<P>
	   Closer to the current fashion scene, the Gattinoni label Monday dipped into
filmmaking and even politics. Reacting to the finale of the show -- a male model
dressed in a white angel's gown -- actress Marisa Berenson leapt onto the
runway, slapped the model, and then fainted. But not to worry -- it was only
make-believe, a scene being filmed on the spot for a remake of the famed "Blue
Angel."
</P>
<P>
	   During the show, Gattinoni also joined the chorus of international protest
against Joerg Haider by presenting a ball gown with "No" written in bold red
letters over a look-alike of the Austrian far-right political leader. The
fashion crowd applauded.
</P>
<P>
	   With all these outside interests, is there still time for plain old
clothes-making?
</P>
<P>
	   Yes, plenty. And the new trend is just that, a return to well-tailored
styles that look like the ones mother used to wear but with new individuality.
</P>
<P>
	   No one does this better than Miuccia Prada, whose trademark is turning
old-fashioned into ultramodern. Despite that fact that she too spends sleepless
nights following Luna Rossa she turned out a near-perfect collection reminiscent
of the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
	   "I never think retro when I design a collection," the designer said after
the much-applauded show. She admitted that it was her husband back in Milan
several weeks ago for a brief period between regattas who pinpointed the
similarity with the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, neat suits with short jacket and mid-calf panel pleated skirts in
knobby tweeds, coats wide at the bottom but tapered at the waist, diaphanous
slip dresses, fur scarves and open-toed shoes all hark back to that period.
</P>
<P>
	   Sunday evening, Donatella Versace gave her version of the contemporary
signora look. Despite the tight fit and the disco shades, the overall look of
below-the-knee hemlines and trim jackets, silk blouses and wide-legged trousers
showed that Donatella was searching for a softer look than in past seasons.
</P>
<P>
	   Thora Birch, 18-year-old American actress who stars in "American Beauty,"
was a front-row viewer for the Versace show.
</P>
<P>
	   The fun-loving Dolce and Gabbana duo, also showing Sunday, left mom at home
and concentrated on her rock star daughter for their second line D&AMP;G show.
</P>
<P>
	   There was graffiti everywhere, from the walls of the theater to the pattern
of the stockings. Hot pants, polka-dot velvet suits, plasticized raincoats,
pleated skating skirts and fur hoods, all in bright color combined to create a
happy fashion party. No matter that it had little to do with the played-down
look currently featuring on the Milan runway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1750 </TRAILER>
