<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Die in Senegal Tour Bus Attacks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- Separatist guerrillas in Senegal ambushed two tour
buses, killing two soldiers and two tour guides and injuring about 20 European
tourists, Senegalese newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The government-owned newspaper Le Soleil said the attack on the buses
occurred Sunday at Kaliane village near Ziguinchor, the capital of the southern
region of Casamance, where rebels have fought a 16-year war for independence.
</P>
<P>
	   Details of the attack were unclear. Senegalese military officials refused to
confirm the incident, and the identities and nationalities of the tourists were
not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
	   The Casamance region, located about 150 miles south of the capital of Dakar
and known for its forests and beaches, has long been a popular resort
destination for French tourists, who make up the overwhelming majority of
overseas visitors to the region.
</P>
<P>
	   The French Embassy declined to comment on the attack Monday, but the French
government warned its citizens to be ``very prudent'' while traveling in
Casamance, Radio France-Internationale reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The violence followed several rounds of peace talks in December and January
that resulted in a cease-fire accord between rebel and government leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   Senegal's government has refused autonomy for Casamance, which is physically
divided from most of northern Senegal by Gambia. More than 1,200 people on both
sides reportedly have been killed since the rebellion began in 1983.
</P>
<P>
	   The rebel Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance claims the region was
never colonized by the French as part of Senegal, and thus remains independent.
France, Senegal's colonial ruler until 1960, disputes the claim.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday in Ndofane, 120 miles southeast of Dakar, four people were
killed when people alleged to be state party supporters drove cars wildly
through an opposition rally, police said. A 12-year-old boy was among those
killed.
</P>
<P>
	   The violence did not immediately appear linked to growing political tensions
ahead of Senegal's presidential elections on Feb. 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1837 </TRAILER>
