<DOCNO> APW20000221.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Seductive 'Time of the Cuckoo'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    An AP Entertainment Review By MICHAEL KUCHWARA AP Drama Critic
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cries of "gondola, gondola" float seductively throughout
"The Time of the Cuckoo," Arthur Laurents' 1952 drama about a lonely, unmarried
American woman learning about love -- and a whole lot more -- in one of the most
romantic places on Earth, Venice.
</P>
<P>
	   The play, slightly revised by its author, remains a sturdy piece of
entertainment, particularly in this lovely production directed with care by
Nicholas Martin and illuminated by its star, Deborah Monk. The actress portrays
heroine Leona Samish with just the right mixture of heartbreak and heartiness.
Plus a bit of bile, as well.
</P>
<P>
	   The Lincoln Center Theater revival, which opened Monday, looks great, too.
Designer James Noone's leafy garden setting of the Pensione Fioria resembles an
Italian Eden, with an inviting backdrop of tan stone houses climbing up the back
wall of the Mitzi Newhouse Theater.
</P>
<P>
	   It is in this tranquil oasis that Laurents plunks down a cross-section of
squabbling American tourists who discover that some things are just done
differently in Italy than back home.
</P>
<P>
	   There are the youngsters, an opportunistic painter (Adam Trese), not above
cooing up to a local comtessa if it means a commission, and his bewildered wife
(Ana Reeder), who was in Firenze for two days before she realized it was
Florence.
</P>
<P>
	   In the hands of such pros as Tom Aldredge and Polly Holliday, a crotchety,
older husband and wife skirt becoming stereotypes. The performers turn obvious
moments of domestic bickering into winning, comic diversions. Their togetherness
contrasts nicely with the singleness of Leona who desperately wants to be part
of a twosome, any twosome.
</P>
<P>
	   Leona's spirits rise when she meets Renato Di Rossi, a courtly shopkeeper
who charms her with his manners and the offer of a good exchange rate for lira
on the black market. Romance blossoms briefly, but then Leona learns the man is
married, although the affection died years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   A few potent martinis -- this is the 1950s and everyone drinks a lot more
than they should -- and a bitterness comes out. Not only bitterness but the fear
at trying something new, something at which she might fail.
</P>
<P>
	   Leona plays it safe, using propriety as an excuse for not living life to the
fullest, a philosophy the playwright obviously endorses.
</P>
<P>
	   Laurents gives this sermon to Signora Fioria, a worldly wise woman who
presides over the guest house. It's not as preachy as it might sound,
particularly in the hands of the wonderful Cigdem Onat, who plays this savvy
philosopher to perfection.
</P>
<P>
	   Fioria has been around the block more than once, and she has stopped along
the way to enjoy her journey. The woman embodies a philosophy that Leona has
trouble accepting: "To make myself see what is here and now; then to accept it,
pleasant or unpleasant; and then, then to try to make it a bit sweeter, a bit
closer to what I would like it to be."
</P>
<P>
	   Leona destroys her chances with Di Rossi, portrayed with plain-spoken charm
by Olek Krupa. At least the woman realizes her mistake, something that gives
Laurents' play a melancholy, yet almost valiant tinge by the time the curtain
falls.
</P>
<P>
	   Monk, wearing a pony tail and a wide grin, follows some formidable and
vastly different ladies in the role of Leona. Shirley Booth was the original on
Broadway; Katharine Hepburn starred in the much altered film version, retitled
"Summertime."
</P>
<P>
	   Yet Monk, who can be funny and touching at the same time, makes the role her
own. Watch her hilariously trying to mime a message to an uncomprehending
Italian servant or, in the play's most dramatic scene, drunkenly striking back
at a perceived hurt. The woman commands the stage. This "Time of the Cuckoo"
makes for potent and compelling theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1842 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
