<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Island police arrest man linked to Peddie School sex attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Police on Long Island have arrested a 24-year-old
drifter who Mercer County authorities say is responsible for a knifepoint sex
attack on a 16-year-old prep school student in Hightstown.
<P>
	   Emily J. Hornaday, a spokeswoman for the county prosecutor's office, said
Michael Lee Allen Jr., 24, is charged with a predawn attack at the Peddie School
on Feb. 11. Allen allegedly assaulted and robbed the boy before being chased off
the campus by security officers.
</P>
<P>
	   Allen could face up to 40 years in prison on the New Jersey charges of
aggravated sexual assault with a weapon, armed robbery and other offenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Nassau County police believe Allen is responsible for a series of sex
attacks over the past three years in various jurisdictions around New York City.
He was arrested Friday in East Williston, N.Y. Nassau County authorities laid
out the details at a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   They have charged Allen in a sex attack remarkably similar to the Peddie
School attack. According to police, Allen slipped into a C.W. Post College dorm
at 4 a.m. last July 5 and sexually assaulted a male teen-ager at knifepoint. The
victim was on the Old Brookville campus for a summer baseball camp.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said they caught Allen after tracking his use of credit cards he
stole from the same campus on Jan. 31. Authorities in neighboring Sussex County
and in Dutchess County in upstate New York are considering charges against Allen
for similar school dormitory attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is believed and alleged that he targeted prep schools through the
Internet," Hornaday said, "and that he had actually gotten directions from the
Internet to go to these various places."
</P>
<P>
	   The Peddie School attack occurred at 4:30 a.m. Hightstown Police and Peddie
School officials said they could not tell how Allen entered the dormitory, which
has a security alarm. The campus also has its own security force.
</P>
<P>
	   "The school is actively reviewing its security provisions to make sure
nothing like this happens again," said Sandy Tattersall, Peddie's dean of
students. "I can't recall something like this."
</P>
<P>
	   The coed school, dating to 1864, has about 500 students in grades eight
through 12. About 300 students are housed in seven dormitories on the campus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 1921 </TRAILER>
