<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3d Largest Mexico Airline Bankrupt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's third-largest airline was declared bankrupt on
Monday -- a decision which was widely expected after the government grounded the
heavily indebted cut-rate airline on Nov. 23 following a crash in western
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling makes it less likely that Taesa will ever fly again. The company
had provided the only major competition for jointly owned Mexicana and
Aeromexico, which together have established a near-monopoly in domestic air
travel.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Justino Montes de Oca ruled that the company's financial condition is
unsustainable. The judge will decide later whether, or how, to liquidate the
company's assets, the government news agency Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Taesa officials had hoped to find investors willing to inject fresh capital
into the company, but those efforts were apparently unsuccessful. Only a few,
engineless Taesa jets remained at the Mexico City airport on Monday, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Another small carrier was expected to take over some of Taesa's most popular
routes, such as those linking Mexico City and Guadalajara to the border city of
Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
	   Taesa offered very low fares and sold tickets from booths in supermarkets.
But it was struggling with enormous debt, much of it incurred in the national
debt crisis of early 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   The government grounded TAESA shortly after one of its vintage DC-9 jetliner
crashed Nov. 9 in central Mexico, killing all 13 passengers and five crew
members on board. Investigators blamed the crash on shoddy maintenance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1922 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Judge To Get Cuban Boy Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The judge in the Elian Gonzalez case suffered a mild stroke,
delaying Tuesday's hearing on whether the court has jurisdiction in the boy's
case until a new judge is assigned.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge William M. Hoeveler, 77, was taken to the hospital by
ambulance with slurred speech Sunday, unable to move his right leg and arm, said
Dr. James Stewart, a neurologist at HealthSouth Doctors' Hospital of Coral
Gables.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoeveler, who suffered a mild stroke, ``has continued to show improvement
today and we expect his progress to continue,'' a hospital news release said. He
was in serious but stable condition Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian is at the center of a custody battle involving his relatives in Miami
and his father in Cuba. The Immigration and Naturalization Service has ordered
the 6-year-old boy returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoeveler had planned to hear arguments Tuesday on whether the federal court
can intervene in the case. Chief U.S. District Judge Edward B. Davis said Monday
said he will preside over the hearing, but only for the purpose of informing
lawyers in the case about the assignment of a new judge, and to schedule future
hearings.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis said the new judge will be selected randomly by a computer.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Hoeveler had complained of ``heart racing,'' his wife, Griffin
Hoeveler, told The Miami Herald. A doctor had suggested he go to the hospital
for tests, but Hoeveler declined.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoeveler, a veteran federal judge who presided over the trial of former
Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega, was assigned the Elian case after another
judge withdrew last month because of a possible conflict of interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1937 </TRAILER>
