<DOCNO> APW20000221.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Sets His Sights on Wash.  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID AMMONS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LACEY, Wash. (AP) -- Bill Bradley is shifting his insurgent's campaign to
Washington state in hopes that its independent-minded voters will give him a
lift in next week's nonbinding Democratic presidential primary contest against
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   The former New Jersey senator plans to spend six days in the state with the
West's second-largest bloc of national convention delegates, after California.
Backers say the Feb. 29 showdown could give Bradley a boost heading into the
pivotal round of coast-to-coast contests a week later.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's moving in, starting Wednesday. This is a big deal to him,'' said
state Auditor Brian Sonntag, a populist Democrat who has endorsed Bradley.
``This primary is the only thing going for Democrats between now and Super
Tuesday on March 7.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Evergreen State has been a frequent stop for Gore, who is backed by Gov.
Gary Locke, Sen. Patty Murray, labor unions and most of the state party
establishment. Gore returns Saturday for a Democratic chili feed at the
aeromachinists labor hall in Seattle. The state twice gave strong support to the
Clinton-Gore ticket.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bradley has taken note of the state's independent streak, with primary
victories by Gary Hart, Paul Tsongas and Jerry Brown over establishment
favorites in previous years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The state of Washington and I are in real sync,'' Bradley said recently.
</P>
<P>
	   He says a strong showing in the nonbinding primary could leverage a victory
in the state's Democratic caucuses a week later on March 7, when 94 convention
delegates will be awarded, as well as help his chances in other states that day.
</P>
<P>
	   Stuart Elway, a Seattle-based independent pollster, said Bradley's chances
could hinge on how well Republican Sen. John McCain does among independents. In
Washington, voters do not register by party and may vote for anyone on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley isn't the only presidential candidate with plans to focus on the
state.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain visits Wednesday, with stops in Spokane, Seattle and Bremerton.
Instead of riding on his ``Straight Talk Express'' bus, the campaign will
christen a local vessel the ``USS Straight Talk'' and ply the waters of Puget
Sound between Seattle and Bremerton.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley calls March 7 ``our national primary'' because 16 states hold
primary contests that day, including California, New York and Ohio. He plans to
fly in to Washington state on Wednesday and campaign through Monday, campaign
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   In weekend interviews, Bradley didn't predict victory Feb. 29 but said it's
a golden opportunity for him to ``demonstrate movement.'' Polls have shown him
trailing Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'd love to win, but we want to at least make up some ground,'' Bradley
campaign spokesman Eric Hauser told reporters Monday in New York, where Bradley
and Gore were debating. ``If we can show over the next week that kind of
progress, it will be a huge momentum boost.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley plans to become ``more aggressive, more comparative'' against Gore
on issues ranging from the environment, education and health care to abortion
and gun control, Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said key pieces of Bradley's platform -- overhauling campaign finance
laws, gun control, health care, abortion rights and environmental protection --
resonate strongly with Washington voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Longabaugh, Bradley's state campaign spokesman, called Washington a
``very important battleground'' and noted Gore's ``very sizable resources''
here. ``But he (Gore) doesn't have all of the people, so we're going to take
this campaign straight to them,'' Longabaugh added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 1942 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
