<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bradley To Debate in Harlem  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Warming up for their debut at the Apollo, Al Gore walked
the streets of Harlem enjoying the advantages of being Bill Clinton's vice
president while Bill Bradley questioned Gore's willingness to help people who
don't have health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic presidential rivals were meeting late Monday at the Apollo
Theatre, the Harlem landmark where Ella Fitzgerald was discovered in 1934, in a
90-minute debate on urban and racial issues. The Rev. Al Sharpton called the
nationally televised forum ``the de-marginalization of our concerns as a
community.''
</P>
<P>
	   New York political consultant Bill Lynch, a Gore supporter estimated that
about 35 percent of voters in the state's Democratic primary on March 7 will be
minorities. The non-white vote in the last two contested Democratic primaries
was 20 percent in 1992, and 29 percent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls give Gore a prohibitive lead among minority voters, much of it
inherited from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   Davita Cook, a forensic science student, called after Gore as he and Rep.
Charlie Rangel, D-N.Y., picked their way down Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard,
past the Harlem Farmers Market and Uptown Jean Co., where two-piece sets of
thermal underwear advertised for $5.99.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Do you promise to pick up where Clinton left off? Do you promise to stay
true?'' the woman called out to Gore, who did not respond.
</P>
<P>
	   Cook told a reporter she was voting for Gore ``only because he is following
in Clinton's footsteps; it's Clinton we adore.''
</P>
<P>
	   Such sentiment rankled film director Spike Lee, who said he will star in a
TV ad for Bradley in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Right or wrong, black people think President Clinton can do no wrong. But
I don't think that means we should automatically transfer that allegiance from
Clinton to Al Gore,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jose Pena, an immigrant from Santo Domingo showed off to Gore the voter
registration card that identified him as a Democrat. ``I have three babies. I
need a job,'' the man told Gore in halting English. Gore referred him to a
caseworker in Rangel's local office.
</P>
<P>
	   Across the street, workers removed ``Amateur Night'' from the Apollo marquee
and instead advertised the face-off between Gore and Bradley -- their first
since Gore solidified his front-runner status with wins in Iowa and New
Hampshire. Bradley has since slipped far behind in some polls and is struggling
to build a comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   He and Gore were thrashing out their differences from lecterns just beside
the Apollo's mythical hollowed-out tree stump, which performers from comedian
Chris Rock to musician James Brown traditionally rub for luck before taking the
stage.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley aides promised a more combative candidate for the two-week sprint to
``Super Tuesday'' when more than a dozen states will vote. Bradley scheduled a
speech on Tuesday on Long Island that was being billed as the kickoff of an
effort to expose inconsistencies and dishonesty in Gore's record.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore campaign strategist Bill Knapp dismissed the pumped-up strategy by
saying, ``He's going to throw battery acid around.'' Knapp said Gore's own sharp
critique of Bradley and his agenda was different because Gore is ``just
defending his record and saying what he wants to do as president.''
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Bradley talked tough before 100 or so parents and other local
residents as he campaigned at Brooklyn's P.S. 24 with City Councilman Angel
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, who has proposed a plan for universal access to health insurance,
warned that voters should be skeptical of Gore's criticism of that plan. ``I am
disappointed that Al Gore has attacked and distorted it. It casts doubt on his
commitment to a basic plank in the Democratic platform.''
</P>
<P>
	   Universal health care has been part of the Democratic Party's platform for
nearly 40 years, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Eric Banks, an art teacher at a Brooklyn high school, called Bradley a
little too liberal for his taste. But Banks also said he was voting for Bradley
because, ``He's more open-minded than Gore.''
</P>
<P>
	   Among the Clinton administration achievements for which Gore sought a share
of credit on Monday were the federal ``empowerment zone'' investments that have
attracted businesses to formerly rundown urban centers like the main street in
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
	   As Gore briefly ducked into an Old Navy store to ask shoppers for their
votes, aides told reporters that Harlem was one of the empowerment zones that
Gore worked on with Rangel.
</P>
<P>
	   Omitted was a crucial piece of legislative history: that it was Bradley who,
as a senator from New Jersey in 1993, wrote the blueprint for the empowerment
zones and -- with Rangel, then-Rep. Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois and New York
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan -- was instrumental in pushing the legislation
through Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 2010 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyanide Leaking in Northwest Romania  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Melting snow brought cyanide to seven wells near a
gold mine that first leaked the poison nearly three weeks ago, contaminating
rivers in central Europe, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Tons of cyanide-laced water spilled from a containment reservoir operated by
the Aurul gold mine near Baia Mare on Jan. 30, spreading into the Tisza and
Danube rivers and killing tons of fish and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
	   Following a recent thaw in the Baia Mare area, more cyanide has apparently
seeped into the wells of the nearby village of Bozanta Mare, Romanian officials
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Andrei Muresan, head of the Health Authority in Baia Mare, said villagers
have been warned about the contamination and have been provided with water for
themselves and for domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, local authorities in counties along the Danube River shut down
water pumps supplying water from the Danube as the cyanide wave approached their
localities.
</P>
<P>
	   The cities of Turnu Magurele and Zimnicea in southern Romania were relying
only on wells and earlier supplies of water.
</P>
<P>
	   At Turnu Magurele, some 78 miles southwest of Bucharest, cyanide
concentration Monday afternoon was 9.4 times more than the acceptable level in
Romania for human consumption.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities in the eastern Romania at the town of Cernavoda, 94 miles east
of Bucharest, said they would close the gates separating the Danube from the
channel that links it to the Black Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 2012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Pardoned After 39 Years  </HEADLINE>
   By G. STEPHEN BIERMAN Jr. Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton granted a full pardon Monday to Preston
King, who fled to England 39 years ago to avoid a prison sentence for draft
evasion.
</P>
<P>
	   King was a graduate student when he fled from Albany, Ga., in 1961 after
being sentenced to serve 18 months in prison. He is now a chairman of political
science at Lancaster University in England.
</P>
<P>
	   King refused to report for an Army physical until an all white draft board
in Georgia addressed him as ``Mr.,'' as they did white draftees. He noted that
the board addressed him as ``Mr. Preston King'' before learning he was black and
``Preston'' after that.
</P>
<P>
	   The full pardon means King is free to return to the United States for the
funeral this week of his brother, Clennon King, who died Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
	   King could not be reached Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the years, he was unable to attend the funerals of his parents or other
relatives for fear of arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   His supporters, who now include the federal judge who sentenced him to an
18-month term, had made a special appeal to Clinton to pardon King in time for
him to attend the dedication of a new federal courthouse under construction in
Albany that is named for another brother, civil rights attorney C.B. King.
</P>
<P>
	   The death of Clennon King moved the process up.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He has paid a big price,'' wrote retired U.S. District Judge William A.
Bootle, now 96, in a letter to Clinton last year. ``To lock him up today would
amount to overkill.''
</P>
<P>
	   The now racially mixed city council in Albany also supported a pardon, as
did the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, the 63-year-old King, spoke about the campaign to pardon him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After 38 years, I'm still unable to return home,'' he said then. ``I'm
still subject to the threat of arrest and harassment by federal authorities. I
am still unable to visit my relations, the graves of my mother and father and
brothers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
