<HEADLINE> Trimble Chides Sinn Fein  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Protestant leader in the Northern Ireland peace process
visited the White House on Monday and chided Sinn Fein and the Irish Republican
Army for doing ``absolutely nothing'' about disarming paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were fully aware of the situation,'' Ulster Unionist Party leader
David Trimble said after a brief meeting with White House national security
adviser Sandy Berger. ``I was astonished at the end of January to discover that
they've done absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
	   A British overseer in Northern Ireland suspended the nascent power-sharing
government this month to prevent a collapse over the IRA's refusal to give up
its weapons.
</P>
<P>
	   Trimble said he and Berger traded views of the current stalemate. He said he
was optimistic that the peace process can still proceed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think we are hoping that we can bounce back from this situation as
quickly as possible but it can't be done without a clear action or response from
the public,'' Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton has been closely involved in the Northern Ireland peace
effort, which he counted as a success until two weeks ago. Clinton said last
week he has frequent conversations with both sides, but has said little about
substantive ideas to resume local government in Northern Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
