<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain Look To Mich. Primary  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) -- Pointing toward Tuesday's second key primary clash in
four days, John McCain accused George W. Bush of waging a campaign of
``character assassination.'' The front-runner aimed his public barbs at Bill
Clinton and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   In the heart of auto country, Bush cited comments Gore made years ago in a
book critical of the internal combustion engine. ``I look forward to him
campaigning up here and saying, 'My vision for America is one where you won't be
working,''' Bush said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the Texas governor's public focus on the general election, his
campaign continued to run television commercials critical of McCain in advance
of Tuesday's Michigan primary.
</P>
<P>
	   The two campaigns also traded charges of phoning voters to criticize their
rivals. Surrogates for the candidates contacted voters as well, including in a
recording by religious broadcaster Pat Robertson, who attacked a McCain campaign
official as a ``vicious bigot who wrote that conservative Christians in politics
are anti-abortion zealots, homophobes and would-be censors.''
</P>
<P>
	   Legitimate pollsters were out in force, and all said the race was very
close, within the margin of the polls' own potential sampling error.
</P>
<P>
	   The stakes were high for both men, but higher for McCain, whose campaign can
ill afford another setback like the one in South Carolina last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, McCain was hoping for a Michigan victory to restart his campaign
momentum and the flow of contributions that followed his big win in the leadoff
New Hampshire primary. McCain's home state of Arizona is voting Tuesday, too,
but most eyes are on Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has said that even if he loses, he'll stay in the race at least until
March 7. That's when California, New York, Ohio and many other states vote in
the biggest night of the primary season.
</P>
<P>
	   At a morning appearance Monday before an overflow crowd in Traverse City,
McCain used some of his harshest words to date in describing the Bush operation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Reject this negative campaigning. Reject this character assassination,''
he said. ``Reject the low road to the presidency and support the high road.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush slapped McCain only when asked by reporters during the day. Questioned
about the Arizona senator's promise to break the ``iron triangle'' of lobbyists,
money and legislation, Bush said, ``He talks about the iron triangle in
Washington D.C. He's been ringing that iron triangle like a dinner bell'' -- a
reference to McCain's fund raising.
</P>
<P>
	   For the most part, though, Bush sought to give the impression of a man
looking ahead to the fall campaign, not someone struggling with the nitty-gritty
of a determined primary challenger.
</P>
<P>
	   In a speech to the Economic Club of Detroit, he touted education reform, a
biennial budget, tax reform and steps to reduce frivolous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I know we're talking about great economic times but no generation should
ever take prosperity for granted,'' he said. ``My job as your future president
is not to think about the Dow Jones today. My job is to look down the road.''
</P>
<P>
	   As for Clinton, he accused the president of missing opportunities for
expanded overseas trade and said, ``I'm going to seize the moment when I become
president.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush made a morning stop at an elementary school, where students were
dressed as presidents to mark the federal holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   In the school library, Bush listened to a speech by Jaclyn Romero, 9, who
was dressed as former president Bush, and by Lauren Fendt, who was dressed as
John Quincy Adams, who followed his father's footsteps into the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's a chance there may be another father and son,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also traveled to a high school, where he likened himself to the Star
Wars character, Luke Skywalker, ``trying to get out of the Death Star. ...
They're all against me, (Michigan) Governor Engler, Governor Bush, all the
governors, all the senators. But we're gonna kill 'em, right, we're gonna get
'em.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush indeed traveled during the day with Engler, one of numerous GOP
governors around the country who helped establish the Texas chief executive as
front-runner in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was joined at his stops by state Sen. Joe Schwarz, who proudly told
audiences he was the only member of his party in the Legislature to break ranks
and join the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was defeated handily in South Carolina after he first launched
negative ads against Bush. When McCain's internal polling showed an erosion of
support, he then stopped, leaving the field clear for the attacks against him.
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan is different: McCain has refrained from attacking Bush in campaign
commercials.
</P>
<P>
	   His hopes for victory lie in his appeal for crossover votes from
independents and some Democrats drawn to his message of reform. But his aides
are worried about the impact of Bush's commercials.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We already have reports of push polls, negative mail pieces; it's hard to
miss the false TV ads,'' Schwarz said in a statement issued by the campaign.
``We're not going to let Bush get away with this shadow campaign in Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
	   In rebuttal, the Bush campaign said McCain's operation was making negative
calls, including one that warns voters not to be ``fooled by George Bush's
negative smear campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush campaign denied any knowledge of the Robertson call, aimed at
former senator Warren Rudman of New Hampshire, McCain's national campaign
chairman. Rudman angered leaders of the religious right in 1995 by defending
retired Gen. Colin Powell against their attacks over abortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
