<DOCNO> APW20000221.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Gets $15.2M in Privacy Suit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PAYNE, Ala. (AP) -- A jury awarded a top state senator $15.2 million in
damages Monday, deciding that his privacy had been invaded by an investigation
by an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic Sen. Lowell Barron, the Senate president pro tem, said Alfa
insurance tried to dig up dirt to get him to support a company vice president
for a seat on the University of Auburn Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
	   Barron, an Auburn trustee, started crying after the verdict and said, ``It
will have a very positive impact on the political process and the future of this
state.''
</P>
<P>
	   The jury decided on $200,000 in compensatory damages and $15 million in
punitive damages against Alfa insurance, the Alabama Farmer's Federation and
former executives Goodwin Myrick and John Dorrill.
</P>
<P>
	   Barron's attorney, Jere Beasley, said the verdict would rein in special
interest groups.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is going to do more to clean up Alabama politics than anything that
has happened in the past 50 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Alfa spokeswoman Debra Davis said an appeal is planned.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We regret that an issue involving the review of public records or the
interviewing of acquaintances of an elected official was viewed in a threatening
manner and wound up in court,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
