<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Kurds Protest Detentions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Some 1,500 people rallied in the largest city in the
overwhelmingly Kurdish southeast to protest the detention of three Kurdish
mayors by Turkish authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   Protesters in Diyarbakir dispersed peacefully after the demonstration to
show support for the mayors of the pro-Kurdish People's Democracy Party who were
detained by police for allegedly having ties to Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   The detentions follow meetings that the mayors had in Europe and Turkey with
European politicians who are demanding cultural rights for Kurds, a call that
the People's Democracy Party and Abdullah Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party, or
PKK, both back.
</P>
<P>
	   Turkey has said it will never negotiate with Ocalan's rebels and is wary of
granting minority rights to Kurds, who are banned from teaching or broadcasting
in Kurdish.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement released in Rome, the PKK said, ``the Kurdish people and
democratic public opinion, both at home and abroad, must not remain in silence
in the face of the arrests.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our people who have elected the mayors must embrace them and must respond
through democratic action,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Private NTV television said the prosecutor's office in Diyarbakir accused
the mayors of holding meetings in Europe as part of a campaign to pressure
Turkey on the Kurdish issue and declare a general amnesty for Kurdish rebels,
including Ocalan, who is on death row in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
	   NTV also said that the mayors were accused of having contacts with rebels
during 20 recent visits to Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   A government statement Saturday said the mayors were accused of extorting
money from citizens, gathering conscripts in Europe for the rebels and
establishing a network of communication between rebels and imprisoned comrades.
</P>
<P>
	   The European Union is demanding that Turkey improve its human rights record
and grant cultural rights to Kurds before it can become a member.
</P>
<P>
	   The pro-Kurdish party, which swept April mayoral elections in 37
southeastern cities and towns, has campaigned for a peaceful settlement to
fighting in the southeast between the PKK and Turkish soldiers and the
recognition of cultural rights. Prosecutors are trying to close the party,
saying it is a front for rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 2053 </TRAILER>
