<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Government Admits 51 Grant Recipients Folded
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Human Resources Department handed out more than $9
million in job creation grants between 1996 and 1999 to 51 companies that went
bankrupt or otherwise closed shop before the projects were completed, federal
records show.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials insist the failure rate was an acceptable one considering more
than 1,000 grants were awarded over those three years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's about a five-per-cent rate of bankruptcy,'' David Good, an assistant
deputy minister at Human Resources, told a briefing Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   He noted it can be a ``challenge'' to make a go of a business in depressed
regions with high unemployment rates -- the kind of areas primarily targeted by
the Transitional Jobs Fund and its successor, the Canada Jobs Fund.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If you compare it to other rates of small- and medium-sized industries in
areas of high unemployment ... five per cent does not seem like an excessive
number.''
</P>
<P>
	   There are thousands of business and personal bankruptcies each year. The
latest monthly statistics, for October 1999, showed more than 6,900 across
Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   Records released by Human Resources showed the 51 grants recipients that
went out of business were originally slated to receive $15 million in funding.
</P>
<P>
	   Bureaucrats estimated that would create more than 2,400 jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, some $9.17 million in federal cash was actually paid to the firms
before they folded.
</P>
<P>
	   The department credited that spending with temporarily creating 751 jobs.
But all of them disappeared -- along with any pre-existing jobs at the same
companies -- when business ceased.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials offered no estimate of the net loss of jobs once the financial
dust had settled.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
British Columbia Supreme Strikes Down Tobacco Suit
</P>
<P>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The provincial government's lawsuit
against tobacco companies can't go ahead because it's based on a provincial law
that is unconstitutional, the British Columbia Supreme Court has ruled.
</P>
<P>
	   Several provinces have been watching the British Columbia action with a view
to launching similar suits of their own. Some are already in the works.
</P>
<P>
	   The court decision, released Monday by the British Columbia parties involved
Monday, said sections of the provincial law try to lump all the tobacco
companies together while ignoring the fact they are federally incorporated and
individual.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I find the Tobacco Damages and Health Care Costs Recovery Act to be
inconsistent with the provision of the Constitution of Canada'' and is beyond
the jurisdiction of the province, wrote Justice Ronald Holmes.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
A Dozen Canadian Audiovisual Works Preserved
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Oscar Peterson's dazzling jazz performances, or Wayne and
Shuster's hilarious Rinse the Blood Off My Toga sketch may be ingrained in
Canadian memory, but they're quickly fading from the reels of celluloid and
stacks of vinyl.
</P>
<P>
	   A new project jointly funded by federal agencies and private industry has
chosen a dozen favorite Canadian audiovisual classics -- such as Peterson's 1961
The Trio album -- for special preservation.
</P>
<P>
	   Peterson was among the guests at a ceremony Monday on Parliament Hill to
honor those who will have their recordings and films preserved in the
Masterworks program.
</P>
<P>
	   The AV Preservation Trust, which administers the Masterworks program, is
pushing the federal government to make proper storage and archiving a condition
of receiving film and TV production funding or tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
	   Heritage Minister Sheila Copps said Monday that idea is already being
studied within her department.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Police Abuse Vs. Aboriginals Spreads to Regina
</P>
<P>
	   REGINA, Sasketchewan (AP) -- A racial firestorm engulfing Saskatoon police
over allegations that officers mistreated aboriginals -- possibly leading to
several deaths -- has spread to Regina.
</P>
<P>
	   The Regina police service is investigating a complaint by a native man that
two of its officers dumped him on the outskirts of town last summer as
punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   The story is similar to an allegation made last week by a Saskatoon man who
says he was dropped off on the edge of that city by police.
</P>
<P>
	   The RCMP are investigating the earlier complaint as well as suggestions
Saskatoon police may have been involved in the deaths of up to four aboriginal
men -- two of whom were found frozen outside the city.
</P>
<P>
	   Sgt. Dave Wyatt of Regina police said his department's internal affairs unit
is handling the latest complaint.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   Gun-Control Opponents Appear at Hearing
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Eight provinces and territories ganged up on Ottawa at an
unusually lively court hearing Monday on whether the federal government has
gutted their power to make law.
</P>
<P>
	   The provinces, supported by the gun lobby, are contesting Ottawa's ability
to implement a national gun-control system that forces owners to get licenses
and register their weapons. They say guns are private property and should be
regulated by the provinces.
</P>
<P>
	   The two-day Supreme Court of Canada hearing began with a presentation by
Alberta, which sparked the legal wrangling in 1998 when it unsuccessfully
challenged the system at its own court of appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyer Roderick McLennan told the nine Supreme Court justices that an
existing handgun registry has failed to stop criminals from using them to commit
crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   The matter before the court is a narrow one, a constitutional question on
whether Ottawa has the power to pass regulatory laws controlling ordinary guns.
</P>
<P>
	   Early on, judges took issue with lawyers' insistence on discussing whether
the gun registry and licensing system works.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It seems to me that that's an argument for Parliament. If you were in
Parliament, you could make that, but you're not in Parliament now,'' said Chief
Justice Beverley McLachlin.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I share some of the concerns that have already been expressed that how
effective the law is going to be is really not before us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
