<HEADLINE> Cop Killed in Mexican Coffee Protest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- A state police commander was
killed and several people were injured in a clash Monday involving farmers
protesting low prices for coffee, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The farmers in Yajalon, about 40 miles north of here, accused local
officials of shortchanging them on the price paid for their coffee crops, said
Attorney General Eduardo Montoya. Coffee is a major crop in Chiapas, Mexico's
southernmost state.
</P>
<P>
	   Montoya said a protest march in the town led to a clash at the police
headquarters as protesters armed with clubs and rocks fought with agents, who
fired bullets and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
	   Police Commander Rodrigo Ortega was killed and several people were injured
by rocks and clubs.
</P>
