<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sotheby's announces new chairman, president  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The venerable auction house Sotheby's announced Monday
that its chairman and president have resigned under pressure from a U.S.
Department of Justice investigation into alleged antitrust violations.
<P>
	   A. Alfred Taubman has stepped down as chairman of Sotheby's Holdings Inc.
and will be replaced by former Columbia University President Michael Sovern, the
auction house's board of directors said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
	   Taubman, who acquired the company in 1983, retains his controlling interest
in the company and a seat on its board of directors.
</P>
<P>
	   "While this clearly is not an easy decision for me, I have determined that
it is time for me to step down from my role as chairman," Taubman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Diana D. Brooks will be replaced as president and chief executive officer of
Sotheby's by William Ruprecht, who has been managing director of Sotheby's North
and South America since 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am very proud of the achievements and initiatives that Sotheby's has
undertaken in recent years and I am confident that in the future it will build
upon its great franchise and reputation for excellence," Brooks said. "My
decision is a very difficult one, but I have taken it in the best interests of
the company and of my colleagues."
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Justice began an investigation in 1997 into auction houses
including Sotheby's and its main rival, Christie's, focusing on alleged
price-fixing in the commissions paid to sellers.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1995, Christie's replaced its longstanding 10 percent commission to
sellers with a sliding scale of 2 percent to 10 percent, and Sotheby's soon
adopted a similar policy.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sherman Antitrust Act prohibits collusion in such arrangements as
illegal restraint of trade, punishable by fines and imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
	   Sotheby's has also been hit with several civil lawsuits from clients
charging collusion between the two auction houses and shareholder class action
complaints alleging failure to disclose the alleged agreements and their impact
on Sotheby's financial conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   Sotheby's said in its statement that it "has recently met with the
Department of Justice in order to discuss a prompt and appropriate resolution of
this investigation, which will allow the company to put this difficult matter
behind it."
</P>
<P>
	   A spokesman for Sotheby's said he could not comment on the relationship
between the resignations and the antitrust probe.
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Justice said last month that Christie's had been given
conditional amnesty in the investigation after supplying the department with new
information on its practices.
</P>
<P>
	   Sotheby's traces its roots to the firm of Samuel Baker, a London bookseller
who first held an auction of rare books in 1744.
</P>
<P>
	   The company now operates in 38 countries, with principal salesrooms in New
York and London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 2205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Rise in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was higher against the yen early Tuesday amid
continued bullish sentiment toward the greenback. Japanese stocks posted
moderate gains.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 111.28 yen, up 0.70 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also
above its late London level of 111.22 yen overnight. U.S. markets were closed
Monday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 103.29 points, or 0.53
percent, to 19,647.04 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the average
closed down 245.28 points, or 1.23 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar moved higher as investors in Europe bought
dollars in early Asian trading Tuesday after a quiet session Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar in recent weeks has been gaining ground against the yen amid
sentiment that Japan's economic recovery is not as firm as previously thought.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.80 yen, up from 109.37 yen
late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started slightly higher following Monday's steep
fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors were cautious over uncertainty about the direction of New York
markets. On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 295.05 points, or
2.8 percent, to close at 10,219.52.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 3.75 points, or 0.22 percent, to 1,684.47. The TOPIX closed down
39.05 points, or 2.27 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8200
percent from Monday's finish of 1.8000 percent. Its price fell 0.17 point to
98.97. (km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
