<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michael Ross penalty hearing to begin Tuesday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - There's no question Michael Ross is a rapist
and a murderer.
<P>
	   He's admitted it. He's been convicted of it.
</P>
<P>
	   And now a jury must decide if he should die for it.
</P>
<P>
	   The long-awaited, long-delayed penalty hearing for Ross is scheduled to get
underway Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury must decide if Ross deserves life in prison or the death penalty
for killing four teen-age girls in New London County in 1983 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross, 40, already is serving two life sentences for killing two other women
in Windham County. He's also admitted to killing two women in New York, but he
has not been prosecuted for these deaths.
</P>
<P>
	   When Ross was convicted of the four killings and sentenced to death in 1987,
it was the first time Connecticut had someone on death row since the U.S.
Supreme Court allowed capital punishment to resume in 1976.
</P>
<P>
	   Since then, Ross' case has taken wild twists through the legal system that
have infuriated the victims' families and set new precedents for how death
penalty cases are treated.
</P>
<P>
	   The case has been before the state Supreme Court three times. Ross is on his
fourth Superior Court judge and second prosecution team.
</P>
<P>
	   He's also been through two sets of defense lawyers, and for a while, the
Cornell University graduate with an IQ of 122 represented himself.
</P>
<P>
	   He asked to be executed in 1994 before his first Supreme Court appeal - an
appeal that is automatic in death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
	   The high court upheld the conviction but overturned the death sentence
because prosecutors withheld from the jury a letter written by a psychiatric
expert. In it, the expert cast doubt on his earlier claim that Ross did not
suffer from a disorder that would make him incapable of handling violent sexual
impulses.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1995, Ross tried to sign his life away in a deal with prosecutors, saying
he wanted to spare his victims' families another grueling trial. The current
judge on the case, Judge Thomas Miano, rejected the pact as illegal.
</P>
<P>
	   In November 1998, Ross tried to kill himself with an overdose of
prescription medicine. Ross also has asked to be castrated and went on a hunger
strike in protest of the appeals process that has delayed his execution.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross had spent his years in court writing everything from letters to
reporters and op-ed pieces to an article that was published in The Journal of
Psychiatry &AMP; Law.
</P>
<P>
	   His pen has been silent for more than a year since Miano issued a gag order.
The order also bars prosecutors, defense attorneys and possible witnesses,
including relatives of Ross' victims, from speaking about the case outside of
court.
</P>
<P>
	   Some relatives of Ross' victims are expected to testify at the hearing about
the brutal way the young women were killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross captured his victims as they walked along quiet, deserted roads in
eastern Connecticut. He raped most of them, then flipped them over onto their
stomachs and strangled them.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1982, Tammy Williams, 17, of Brooklyn, and 23-year-old Debra Smith
Taylor, of Griswold, were killed. Ross pleaded guilty to their killings in 1985
and got two life sentences in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1983, 19-year-old Robyn Stavinsky, of Norwich, an athlete described in
court papers as a "very carying, trusting person," was raped and murdered.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross told investigators Stavinsky was stronger than other girls he had
strangled and that his hands cramped from gripping her around the neck. Medical
examiners said the strangulation may have taken as long as 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   The following year, Wendy Baribeault, 17, of Jewett City, was found dead
under a pile of stones in the woods off Route 12.
</P>
<P>
	   Baribeault, who was described as a "caring and sensitive young lady,"
struggled with Ross as he dragged her over two stone walls. He raped her, then
sat on top of her and strangled her, his hands again cramping so that he had to
relax them before resuming the hold around her neck.
</P>
<P>
	   On Easter Sunday 1984, Ross killed two 14-year-old friends, Leslie Shelley
and April Brunais, both of Griswold.
</P>
<P>
	   April was tall for her age and described as a "sensitive girl concerned with
others," while Leslie, described as "shy, withdrawn and a quiet little girl,"
was petite and weighed less than 90 pounds.
</P>
<P>
	   They were returning to Wendy's home from a walk to Jewett City along Route
138 when Ross offered them a ride. When he drove past their destination, the
girls became upset and April pulled out a knife.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross wrested the knife from April and drove to a secluded area off a dirt
road. He made April take off her jeans and cut them into strips, which he used
to bind the girls. He raped April and strangled her, then strangled Leslie.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors contend Ross should get the death penalty because the killings
were especially cruel and that Ross was indifferent to his victims' suffering.
Prosecutors also argue Ross was in control of his actions and killed his victims
so they could not send him back to jail, as did a 1982 assault victim in Ohio
identified him.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense lawyers claim Ross' history and psychological problems mean that he
should be spared execution.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross was abused as a child on his family's egg farm in Brooklyn, where one
of his jobs was killing malformed and sick chicks.
</P>
<P>
	   He has been diagnosed with a mental disorder called "sexual sadism," which
urges him to repeatedly engage in violent sexual activity. An expert found Ross'
brain has a smaller-than-average cerebellum - a sign of behavioral deficiency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-21-00 2215 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bradley Debate in Harlem  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an angry Harlem debate, Bill Bradley accused Al Gore of
trying to conceal his record as ``a conservative congressman,'' and the vice
president said his rival's tactics ``divide us as Democrats'' instead of dealing
with the Republican enemy in the campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   In the historic Apollo Theatre, to the cheers and sometimes the jeers of a
largely black audience, Gore and Bradley began by promising that they would act
against racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley demanded to know why the vice president hadn't gone down the hall to
get President Clinton to issue an executive order outlawing racial profiling.
Gore shot back that racial profiling practically began in Bradley's New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   The exchange was prompted by the leadoff question, accorded to The Rev. Al
Sharpton. ``Many in our community have to live in fear of both the cops and the
robbers,'' the black activist said, asking how they would deal with police
brutality and racial profiling while avoiding an increase in crime.
</P>
<P>
	   In a high profile case, Amadou Diallo, an unarmed black man, died in a
barrage of 41 police bullets a year ago in his Bronx apartment building. White
police officers say they fired upon him after he refused orders to halt and
appeared to draw a gun, although the black object in his hand was a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said racial profiling is a state of mind in which a policeman sees a
wallet in the hands of a white man as what it is, ``and a wallet in the hand of
a black man as a gun,'' as in the Diallo shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he would issue an executive order against racial profiling, and
would declare ``quite clearly that white Americans can no longer deny the plight
of black Americans.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``If you elect me to the presidency, the first civil rights act of the 21st
century will be a federal law outlawing racial profiling,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said it would cover not only law enforcement but all aspects of American
society.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's asked why the administration has not produced an executive order.
``I am questioning why you haven't done that or why you haven't made this happen
in the past 7 1/2 years,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said Clinton has issued a directive to prepare for an executive order.
``You know racial profiling practically began in New Jersey, senator,'' Gore
shot back. Profiling episodes involving state troopers led New Jersey to appoint
a civilian monitor against the practice.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, asked about reparations from the government to atone for slavery, said
``I believe the best reparation is a good education,'' and affirmative action to
open opportunities to black Americans. He said general reparations would not be
approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley accused Gore of trying to end affirmative action at the federal
level, which the vice president vehemently denied. He said his program for
overhauling the bureaucracy as vice president was against quotas, not
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
	   Reaching across the three feet separating their lecterns, Bradley held out a
sheaf of documents he said documented five votes by Gore between 1979 and 1981
to preserve the tax-exempt status of colleges that racially discriminate.
</P>
<P>
	   In those votes, Gore split with members of the Congressional Black Caucus,
including New York Rep. Charlie Rangel, a leading Gore supporter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You have to face up to this if you're going to be a strong leader,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore refused to take the papers and explained away the votes as ``a vote on
quotas.''
</P>
<P>
	   In turn, he challenged Bradley to explain a 1995 vote that Gore described as
a rejection of expanding minority ownership of broadcast outlets.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley pressed his own point and Gore was jeered when he cut his rival off.
``You're sounding a little desperate because you're trying to build yourself up
by tearing everybody else down,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley wasn't spared boos, either, when he went after Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   He said repeatedly that Gore's record in Congress was that of a
conservative. ``He was a conservative Democrat before he was Bill Clinton's vice
president.'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   In those days, he said, Gore was ``poster boy'' for the opponents of gun
control.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What you see is an elaborate what I call `Gore dance,''' Bradley said.
``It is a dance to avoid facing up to your conservative record.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The problem is these attacks don't solve any problems,'' Gore said. ``They
do divide us as Democrats. They distract us from the real enemy, the right wing
extremists, Confederate flag-waving Republicans, who are trying to roll back the
progress that we have made,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he has the endorsement of organized labor, abortion rights
activists, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and the Congressional Black Caucus. ``Do you
think they all have such poor judgment, Senator Bradley?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What I think is they don't know your record as a conservative Democrat,''
Bradley said, drawing jeers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In my experience the Black Caucus is pretty savvy,'' Gore retorted. ``They
know a lot more than you think they know.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley also pressed his argument that Democrats will suffer for Gore's
involvement in 1996 campaign fund-raising excesses unless the vice president
more fully explains his conduct.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You must be the only Democrat in America who misses Ken Starr,'' Gore told
him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I did not propose a special prosecutor,'' Bradley said. ``I said that the
Democratic party will lose its mantle as a reform party if we don't come to
terms with what happened in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
	   Despite their clashes, Bradley said he would support Gore if he won the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The rivals met on the stage of the landmark Apollo Theater, where Ella
Fitzgerald was discovered in 1934, their 90-minute debate concentrating on urban
and racial issues.
</P>
<P>
	   New York political consultant Bill Lynch, a Gore supporter estimated that
about 35 percent of voters in the state's Democratic primary on March 7 will be
minorities. The non-white vote in the last two contested Democratic primaries
was 20 percent in 1992, and 29 percent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls give Gore a prohibitive lead among minority voters, much of it
inherited from Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 2218 </TRAILER>
