<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Robertson Attacks McCain Official  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   YPSILANTI, Mich. (AP) -- In a recorded message phoned to Michigan voters,
religious broadcaster Pat Robertson attacks an official in John McCain's
campaign as ``a vicious bigot who wrote that conservative Christians in politics
are anti-abortion zealots, homophobes and would-be censors.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``John McCain refused to repudiate these words,'' Robertson added in the
message that was recorded Monday by a Michigan man. Robertson's remarks refer to
former senator Warren Rudman of New Hampshire, who is McCain's national campaign
chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   Rudman angered leaders of the religious right in 1995 by defending retired
Gen. Colin Powell against their attacks over abortion. Rudman also wrote about
the controversy in a book.
</P>
<P>
	   Robertson, founder of the Christian Coalition who ran unsuccessfully for the
Republican presidential nomination in 1988, made no mention of Bush in the brief
message.
</P>
<P>
	   Todd Harris, a McCain spokesman, did not allege any involvement by Bush's
campaign, but said: ``This is exactly the kind of politics that we had hoped we
left behind in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Pat Robertson and (former Christian Coalition director) Ralph Reed hand
delivered Governor Bush's victory to him in South Carolina,'' Harris said. ``The
people of Michigan have an opportunity to repudiate these kinds of negative
smears.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's campaign denied making the calls, and accused the McCain camp and its
allies of running get-out-the-vote phone banks that were critical of the Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are not making any Pat Robertson calls,'' said Bush campaign
spokeswoman Mindy Tucker. ``Our campaign doesn't know anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gene Kapp, a spokesman for Robertson, confirmed that Robertson had recorded
the message but said it had nothing to do with the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was an issues education call that was made on behalf of the Christian
Coalition to members on the Christian Coalition list in Michigan,'' Kapp said
Monday night. ``It was made to get out the vote. It did not endorse or request a
vote for a specific candidate.''
</P>
<P>
	   In 1988, George Bush easily won county caucuses in Michigan, knocking
Robertson off his then-front-runner pace, and the religious leader responded by
staging a losing legal and convention battle for a greater share of the state's
77 nominating delegates.
</P>
<P>
	   The McCain telephone calls urge voters to support McCain in Tuesday's GOP
primary. One call says McCain is more conservative than Bush, who is criticized
for spending increases in Texas where he is governor. The other warns voters not
to be ``fooled by George Bush's negative smear campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   Adrienne Karns, an accountant from Birmingham, Mich., said in an interview
that she received a recorded call telling her Catholics should vote for McCain.
She said she did not believe the call was endorsed by McCain's campaign, and
instead was sponsored by an outside group.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It started off saying it was a 'Catholic voters' alert,''' Karns said,
noting the call mentioned Bush's appearance at Bob Jones University in South
Carolina and school's perception as being anti-Catholic. ``It said McCain had
not been to the university, and he was a friend of all Catholics, and all
Catholics should vote for John McCain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Karns said she was voting for Bush and that the call would not change her
mind.
</P>
<P>
	   Riding a wave of conservative support, Bush defeated McCain in South
Carolina's GOP primary Saturday, leaving McCain in a fight for survival in
Michigan's contest.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has criticized Bush in recent days for running a negative campaign in
South Carolina and now in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   The Robertson message came to light when a Michigan voter, Jim Pouillon,
contacted McCain's campaign to express displeasure over having received the
call.
</P>
<P>
	   In a telephone interview, Pouillon said he is a member of the anti-abortion
group Operation Rescue and that he stood outside a high school where McCain
appeared Monday displaying an anti-abortion sign. But he said of the sentiments
expressed by Robertson, ``This is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
	   The message opens with Robertson saying ``Protect unborn babies and restore
religious freedom once again in America.'' The primary will determine whether
the party nominates a man ``who wants to take First Amendment freedom from
citizens groups while he gives unrestricted power to labor groups,'' he
continues.
</P>
<P>
	   That was a reference to McCain's advocacy of campaign finance legislation to
ban unlimited contributions known as soft money. McCain says his legislation
would also apply to unions and he says he advocates other positions to limit
their use of campaign dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
