<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Feb. 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore-Bradley Debate Is Lively
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In a hard-hitting debate, Democratic presidential campaign
rivals Al Gore and Bill Bradley tonight each denounced racial profiling. They
faced each other at a nationally televised event in Harlem. Bradley demanded to
know why the vice president hadn't convinced President Clinton to issue an order
outlawing racial profiling. Gore said racial profiling practically began in New
Jersey, where Bradley had served as a senator. The Rev. Al Sharpton, a civil
rights leader, called the debate "the de-marginalization of our concerns as a
community."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Clash in Michigan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) -- George Bush, the GOP presidential front-runner,
sought to look beyond the high-stakes primary in Michigan tomorrow vs. John
McCain. At the Economic Club of Detroit, Bush called for education reform, a
biennial budget, tax reform and steps to cut frivolous lawsuits. However, Bush's
campaign kept runing television commercials critical of McCain. McCain, accusing
Bush of "character assassination," urged voters: "Reject the low road to the
presidency."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
MD-80 Jetliner Lands Safely
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- A MD-80 jetliner headed from Las Vegas to Cleveland
landed safely today at the South Bend Airport after its crew had problems
maintaining level flight. No one aboard was injured when Continental Flight 1416
carrying 141 passengers and five crew members made the emergency landing. The
FAA said the crew reported problems with aileron trim, which controls rolling.
Experts were checking the plane, which is similar to the one that crashed Jan.
31 offshore near Los Angeles, killing 88 people on Alaska Airlines Flight 261.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Plans New Peace Offer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Monday his
administration is working on new proposals to break the impasse in peace talks
with the Palestinians. In a speech to U.S. Jewish leaders, Barak said, "We will
try in the next few days to shape a kind of package through contacts with the
Palestinians that would help take the wagon out of where it is right now and put
it back on track." Afterward, he met with U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross, who
was expected to pass along Israeli suggestions to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Judge To Get Cuban Boy Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- The federal judge in the Elian Gonzalez refugee custody case
suffered a mild stroke, delaying tomorrow's hearing on whether the court has
jurisdiction over the Cuban 6-year-old boy until a new judge is assigned. U.S.
District Judge William M. Hoeveler, 77, was taken to the hospital yesterday. He
was in serious but stable condition tonight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Space Shuttle Is Set to Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA has informed space shuttle Endeavour's
astronauts that the backup landing site at Edwards Air Force Base in California
appears to be the "only viable option" for tomorrow's landing. Clouds and high
wind were forecast at Cape Canaveral in Florida. The last time NASA had to
divert a space shuttle to Edwards was in 1996. With their mapping of Earth
completed, the astronauts pulled in a 197-foot radar antenna mast after
struggling with it for two tense hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Peanuts' Creator Schulz Remembered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) -- More than 2,000 people filled an arts center
today to remember Charles Schulz, the late "Peanuts" creator. Cartoonist Cathy
Guisewite and tennis great Billie Jean King were among those on hand. Schulz,
77, died from colon cancer nine days ago just as his final comic strip was being
published. His widow, Jeanne, said the world's most widely syndicated cartoonist
never realized how beloved his creations were until after he decided in November
to end the strip.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iran Reformers Win Seats
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Reformists led in voting for most of Tehran's
parliament seats Monday and looked set to sweep there -- a victory that would
guarantee them a parliamentary majority with dozens of other seats still left to
be decided nationwide. The results sent a clear message to the hard-line clergy
that Iranians are fed up with their 21-year restrictive rule that dictates
day-to-day lives. They were also an endorsement of President Mohamed Khatami,
who has advocated dismantling many social and political restrictions since he
came to power in 1997.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks posted moderate gains on Tuesday. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 103.29 points in early trading.
On Monday, U.S. financial markets were closed for Presidents Day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
St. John's Beats UConn
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- St. John's starting backcourt of Erick Barkley and Bootsy
Thornton outscored its counterparts 42-2 and the Red Storm rolled tonight to
their sixth straight victory, a 79-64 win over No. 22 Connecticut. The Red Storm
is 19-6 and 11-3 Big East. The loss was the fourth in sixth games for the
Huskies (18-8, 7-6).
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
