<DOCNO> APW20000221.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Predators 5, Stars 2  </HEADLINE>
    By TERESA M. WALKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Ville Peltonen scored a goal and added an assist
and Tomas Vokoun stopped 23 shots as the Nashville Predators snapped a six-game
losing skid by beating the Dallas Stars 5-2 on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Nashville hadn't scored more than two goals in a game since Feb. 2, also the
last time it won a game. Cliff Ronning, not invited to the All-Star game earlier
this month, set the tone 26 seconds in when he scored his 21st goal off a
rebound of David Legwand's missed backhander.
</P>
<P>
	   The Stanley Cup champions, who beat Colorado 2-1 at Denver on Sunday, looked
tired. The Stars couldn't get any offense going and had only five shots in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
	   Manny Fernandez shut out the Predators last week and had been giving up just
a league-best 1.74 goals per game. But he allowed two goals within the first
nine minutes as Vitali Yachmenev scored his 12th at 8:49. Fernandez gave up the
most goals scored against Dallas since Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
	   Dallas pulled within 2-1 4:10 into the second when Brenden Morrow backhanded
the puck in off Sylvain Cote's pass from the slot on a power play.
</P>
<P>
	   Nashville answered 33 seconds later when Kimmo Timonen got his eighth goal
off an assist from Peltonen and Sebastien Bordeleau. It got so bad for the Stars
that Vokoun got an assist at 14:53 when he set up Scott Walker who fed Peltonen
on the right wing where he scored for a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
	   Dallas came alive in the third and finished the game outshooting Nashville
25-22. Guy Carbonneau got his eighth goal on a backhander at 1:53, but that was
it as Vokoun had several big saves, including a glove stop off Richard Matvichuk
with five minutes left.
</P>
<P>
	   Patric Kjellberg tied Ronning for the team lead in goals when he scored on a
power play with 1:01 to go.
</P>
<P>
	   The only bright side for Dallas was Brett Hull. He had an assist on Morrow's
goal, giving him 100 points in his 118 games since joining the Stars before last
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-21-00 2311 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000221.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cavaliers 109, Grizzlies 108, OT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CLEVELAND (AP) -- Wesley Person forced overtime with a 3-pointer at the
buzzer and Bob Sura slapped the ball away from Michael Dickerson with three
seconds to play Monday night to preserve Cleveland's 109-108 victory over
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Bryant gave Cleveland its only lead of overtime by converting a
three-point play with 2:01 left. Bryant made a hook shot in the lane, was
fouled, and sank the free throw for a 109-108 advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   Both teams missed chances to score and Vancouver got the ball back with 15
seconds to play. Dickerson caught a pass from Mike Bibby near the top of the
key, and Sura reached in from behind and slapped the ball away.
</P>
<P>
	   Shawn Kemp's 26 points led the Cavaliers, Lamond Murray had 25 and Person
added 18, including five 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
	   Dickerson scored 27 points, including four free throws in the final 9.4
seconds of regulation, to lead Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
	   Dickerson made two foul shots to put the Grizzlies ahead, 100-99. Cleveland
called timeout and set up a shot for Kemp, who drove the lane but misfired badly
with 3.1 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
	   Dickerson grabbed the rebound, was fouled by Danny Ferry and made two more
free throws for a 102-99 advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   After another timeout, Person took an inbounds pass from Andre Miller, faked
Doug West into the air, then tied the score with a 26-foot jumper from the wing.
</P>
<P>
	   Murray already had 17 points with 1:30 left to play in the first quarter,
then did not take another shot for the next 17:21.
</P>
<P>
	   Bibby scored four of his 25 points in overtime for Vancouver.
</P>
</TEXT>
