<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shareholders sue Campbell, allege sham shipments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Several Campbell Soup Co. shareholders have sued the
company, alleging that it set up "sham shipments" of unwanted soup to make its
profits look larger than they were last year, according to a published report.
The company has denied the accusation.
<P>
	   The Philadelphia Inquirer reported in Tuesday's editions that the first
lawsuit, filed last month by the pension fund of New York-based Laborers Local
1298, accused Campbell of having arranged with large resellers to receive their
products at the end of each quarter. These "transactions" were induced by
offering the resellers deep discounts and rebates, the Laborers alleged.
</P>
<P>
	   "Since these customers did not want the product, Campbell arranged for
hundreds of trucks to line up at each of Campbell's four U.S. facilities (in
Ohio, Texas, California and North Carolina) on the last days of each quarter and
physically move product" to other Campbell storage facilities, booking the
transfers as sales, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell denied in meetings with analysts and reporters last week that the
company had set up phony shipments to enable the company to book higher profits
last year.
</P>
<P>
	   At least half a dozen investors have filed similar lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell last month said it was ending a long-term practice of offering
steep quarterly discounts to encourage retailers to stock up. But company
spokesman John Faulkner said Friday there were no improper sales.
</P>
<P>
	   The pension fund's lawsuit said one of the companies that had arranged to
receive Campbell's products in exchange for discounts or rebates was Fleming
Cos. Fleming spokesman Shane Boyd told the newspaper, "Our business with
Campbell's reflects nothing unusual. The goods we paid for, we got. We got
product offered to us at deep discounts, and we bought it."
</P>
<P>
	   The case is pending before U.S. District Judge Joseph E. Irenas in Camden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
