<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Feb. 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bradley Debate in Harlem
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an angry Harlem debate, Al Gore accused Bill Bradley of
attack tactics that "divide us as Democrats," while the challenger described the
vice president as a sometime conservative with a suspect record on affirmative
action. The tone of the argument on the stage of the historic Apollo Theater was
set at the start, when the presidential rivals agreed that they'd both take
steps against racial profiling -- and immediately tried to turn the question
against each other. The 90-minute debate -- the candidates ninth presidential
debate -- was televised by CNN. The largely black audience cheered, applauded,
jeered, sometimes booed. Neither candidate was spared the raucous reactions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Works on New Peace Proposal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Monday his
administration is working on new proposals to break the impasse in peace talks
with the Palestinians. In a speech to U.S. Jewish leaders, Barak said, "We will
try in the next few days to shape a kind of package through contacts with the
Palestinians that would help take the wagon out of where it is right now and put
it back on track." Afterward, he met with U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross, who
was expected to pass along Israeli suggestions to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Threatens Unification or War
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- China warned Monday that it might attack Taiwan if the
island's leaders indefinitely refuse to talk unification. The threat, which came
a month before Taiwan's presidential election campaign, was intended to increase
the pressure on Taiwan's three presidential candidates. Although there was no
immediate reaction from Taiwan's government or the candidates' camps, policy
toward China has been at the center of the campaign. Already this month, China
sailed its newly acquired, destroyer through the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Space Shuttle To Land in California
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA has informed space shuttle Endeavour's
astronauts that the backup landing site at Edwards Air Force Base in California
appears to be the "only viable option" for tomorrow's landing. Clouds and high
wind were forecast at Cape Canaveral in Florida. The last time NASA had to
divert a space shuttle to Edwards was in 1996. With their mapping of Earth
completed, the astronauts pulled in a 197-foot radar antenna mast after
struggling with it for two tense hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Remember 'Peanuts' Creator
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) -- More than 2,000 people filled an arts center
today to remember Charles Schulz, the late "Peanuts" creator. Cartoonist Cathy
Guisewite and tennis great Billie Jean King were among those on hand. Schulz,
77, died from colon cancer nine days ago just as his final comic strip was being
published. His widow, Jeanne, said the world's most widely syndicated cartoonist
never realized how beloved his creations were until after he decided in November
to end the strip.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Higher in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks posted moderate gains on Tuesday. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 103.29 points in early trading.
On Monday, U.S. financial markets were closed for Presidents Day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pistons Scorch Heat 95-87
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Terry Mills had six 3-pointers -- one shy of his
career high -- as the Detroit Pistons, winless in three games since the All-Star
break, beat the Miami Heat 95-87 Monday night. Grant Hill scored 26 points while
Jerry Stackhouse and Lindsey Hunter each had 22 for the Pistons, who have won
three in a row at The Palace and 13 of their past 17 at home. Alonzo Mourning
scored 20 points for Miami despite having his nose broken before fouling out
with 2:24 remaining. Jamal Mashburn added 14 for the Heat, who went 1-3 on their
four-game road trip.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sabres Score 3-2 Victory Over Devils
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Geoff Sanderson scored the winning goal with 3:59 left
in the third period, lifting the Buffalo Sabres to a 3-2 victory Monday night
over the New Jersey Devils. Dixon Ward and Miroslav Satan also scored and
Dominik Hasek made 35 saves for the Sabres, who moved one point ahead of the New
York Rangers for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
The teams, which each have 21 games remaining, will meet Friday night at
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</P>
